{"title_page": "Boing (Spanish TV channel)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n| name              = Boing\n| logofile          = Boing.svg\n| logosize          = 150px\n| launch            = {{Start date and age|df=y|2010|9|1}}\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    = [[576i]] ([[16:9]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| network           = [[Telecinco]]\n| owner             = [[Warner Bros]]. Espa\u00f1a (50%)<br />[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] (50%)\n| founder           = [[Gestevisi\u00f3n Telecinco]]\n| slogan            = ''\u00a1Juntos, mejor!'' (English: ''Better together!'')\n| country           = Spain\n| language          = Spanish \n| broadcast area    = Spain (via terrestrial)\n| headquarters      = \n| web               = [http://www.boing.es/ www.boing.es]\n| sat serv 1        = \n| sat chan 1        = \n| cable serv 1      = \n| cable chan 1      = \n| iptv serv 1       = \n| iptv chan 1       = \n| sister names      = Mediaset Espa\u00f1a:<br />[[Telecinco]]<br />[[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]]<br />[[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity]]<br />[[Energy (TV channel)|Energy]]<br />[[Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n]]<br />Turner Broadcasting System Europe:<br />[[Cartoon Network (Portugal)|Cartoon Network Portugal]]<br />[[Boomerang (Portugal)|Boomerang Portugal]]<br />[[TNT (Spain)|TNT]]<br />[[Turner Classic Movies (Spain)|TCM]]<br />[[CNN International]]<br />WarnerMedia Entertainment:<br />[[HBO (International)#Spain|HBO Espa\u00f1a]]\n}}\n'''Boing''' is a Spanish free-to-air television channel, owned by a joint venture between [[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] and [[Warner Bros.]] through its Spain unit, which was launched in 2010. When [[Cartoonito (Spain)|Cartoonito]] and [[Cartoon Network (Spain)|Cartoon Network]] were shut down on 30 June 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.es/|title=Former Channel|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327012201/http://www.cartoonnetwork.es/|archivedate=27 March 2015}}</ref> many Cartoon Network programmes were moved to Boing, alongside new Boomerang programmes. The shows on the channel are also available in English via a second audio feed, whereas Doraemon uses the original Japanese audio track.\n\nAdditional Boing feeds are available in [[Boing (Italy)|Italy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boingtv.it/|title=Boing Italy}}</ref> [[Boing (France)|France]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boingtv.fr/|title=Boing France}}</ref> and [[Boing (Africa)|Sub-Saharan Africa]], with Cartoon Network and Boomerang also being available in those territories.\n\n==History==\nOn 28 November 2008, Telecinco and Turner<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/1,20081128,9580,1.html</ref>, reached an agreement to introduce a children's programming block on the Telecinco channel, with some 42 hours of weekly programming. Three days later, the Boing drawing container began in [[Telecinco]] and [[Telecinco 2]].\n\nMonths later, on 11 May 2009, Boing went from Telecinco 2 to [[Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n]], of the same group, with the same contents and similar schedules, since Telecinco 2 became [[La Siete]] and changed part of its programming.\n\nOn 2 August 2010, Telecinco announced the launch of Boing as its fourth free-to-air television channel,<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/15944/telecinco-lanza-boing-cuarto-canal-adios-lanueve/</ref> moving from a series container to an open-themed channel dedicated 24 hours a day to the youngest in the house, with Turner star products. In its first weeks of broadcasting, Boing offered a six-hour programming loop that hosted the animations ''[[Geronimo Stilton]]'', ''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]'', ''[[Dinosaur King]]'', ''[[Powerpuff Girls Z]]'', ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'', ''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]'' and ''[[Inazuma Eleven]]'',<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/16098/boing-inicia-emisiones-proximo-1-septiembre/</ref> to incorporate progressively own content in the following weeks in a grid in which, since then, fictions aimed at children and adolescent viewers coexist.\n\nOn 9 August 2010, it began its test broadcasts showing a letter of adjustment and on 23 August a promotional loop of series that would be broadcast in its premiere on 1 September of the same year.<ref>http://www.mundoplus.tv/noticias/?seccion=tv_digital&id=8090</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2010, its official broadcasts began with a programme that included a welcome selection of the Turner factory's star products.<ref>http://www.mundoplus.tv/noticias/?seccion=tv_digital&id=8106</ref> Telecinco's new children's channel premiered with a 0.58% quota. With the arrival of the new channel, ''Boing'', the series container of Telecinco and Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n was renamed ''[[SuperBoing]]'', although on 1 January 2011, it ceased broadcasting on both channels after the merger with [[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]], and its contents were shown exclusively on the Boing channel.\n\nOn 28 November 2010 the channel premiered ''[[Ed, Edd n Eddy's Big Picture Show|La gran pel\u00edcula de Ed, Edd y Eddy]]'', an animated film from the series [[Ed, Edd and Eddy]]. Although its official release was one year and 22 days earlier (6 November 2009) on the private and pay-TV network [[Cartoon Network (Spain)|Cartoon Network]], it was the first film broadcast on Boing and the first feature of a previous series broadcast on the network.\n\nOn 31 May 2011, the cable operator [[ONO (Spain)|ONO]] incorporated the Boing channel in its basic package (which already has 17 children's channels) on dial 64, so all subscribers to the operator have access to that channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/19778/boing-divinity-incorporan-oferta-ono/</ref><ref>http://satcesc.com/web/2011/05/25/la-television-de-ono-incopora-los-canales-divinity-y-boing/</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2011, Boing's creative and advertising group, [[Time Warner]] and [[Publiespa\u00f1a]], changed the channel's corporate image with new advertising blocks, adding animated curtains in the presentation of the series and more information. The logo was also modified to a darker tone and with a spherical shape.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110628220729/http://tecnoociencia.com/2011/06/26/boing-cambia-su-imagen-corporativa-y-su-mosca/</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2011, [[Mediaset Spain]] announced that, from the fourth quarter of the year, Publiespa\u00f1a would launch a commercial policy in the channel with ''Desayuna y merienda con Boing'' containers. Both are presented by the EVA robot.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/20275/robot-eva-presentara-desayuna-con-boing-merienda-con-boing/</ref>\n\nOn 16 August 2011, pay-TV operator [[Movistar TV]] added the Boing channel on its 63 dial. It later changed to 69 dial. In 2015 it became Movistar+, so it is now on 97 dial.\n\nOn 7 September 2011, Boing's official website renewed the content of the website, transforming it to its new corporate image and creating new sections. These sections include a games section, a series section, a video and photo portal and a blog where users are informed daily of the new releases that come to the channel.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120114233421/http://www.boing.es/blog/boinges-%C2%A1una-nueva-web-para-empezar-bien-el-curso</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2011, Grupo Zeta launched the first issue of Boing Magazine to the kiosks. After an agreement between Grupo Zeta and the communication groups Turner Broadcasting System and Mediaset Espa\u00f1a, the publication was born with the same drive as the young children's channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/21265/sale-mercado-revista-boing/</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, 4 February 2012, Mediaset Spain's children's channel reached its daily audience record with a 1.8% screen share, and was even one tenth (1.9%) away from [[Neox]], [[Atresmedia]]'s thematic channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/audiencias/2012-02-04/</ref> One month after making history, on 3 March of the same year, it obtained a 2% screen share, two tenths away from its main competitor Disney Channel (2.2%).<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/23921/peppa-pig-cuela-mas-vistos-dia-gran-112-clan/</ref> Finally, weeks after reaching the daily maximum with a quota of 2.0%, on Saturday 14 April it repeated its success by giving the channel an audience share of 2.5% of the screen in total day and reaching the historic maximum since its premiere.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/24505/fdf-lidera-prime-time-cadenas-tematicas-tdt-la-que-se-avecina/</ref> Almost two months later, on 2 June, the children's channel of Mediaset Spain broke a new record on Saturday, giving the group a quota of 2.6% daily screen share.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/25289/phineas-y-ferb-arrasa-manana-disney-channel-impresionante-10/</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Boing achieved the monthly maximum in DTT with a share of 2.1%, surpassing its great competitor [[Disney Channel (Spain)|Disney Channel]] by 3 tenths.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/26192/audiencias-maximo-mayoria-cadenas-tdt-mediaset-fdf-boing-divinity-energy/</ref> The channel gets the best result of its history thanks to films such as ''[[Ice Age]]''. In terms of audience, it is the second most watched channel among children from 4 to 12 years with a commercial target of 14.1%.\n\nSince November 2015, one month after being awarded a new HD channel by the government, Mediaset broadcast Boing in HD on a temporary basis until 7 January 2016<ref>http://perdidosenlatele.com/2015/11/28/mediaset-adjudica-a-boing-su-nueva-licencia-en-hd/</ref> Being replaced by [[Energy HD]], and this was replaced on 21 April]by [[Be Mad TV]], the new channel of Mediaset Spain.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/52400/mediaset-espana-boing-hd-energy-hd-espera-lanzar-nuevo-canal/</ref><ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/55140/be-mad-tv-puesto-fecha-inicio-emisiones/</ref><ref>http://www.adslzone.tv/2016/03/18/be-mad-tv-sera-el-nombre-del-nuevo-canal-de-mediaset/</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2016, the channel renewed its corporate image, adapting to the worldwide image of the channel that premiered its [[Boing (Italy)|Italian version]] on 7 March of the same year.\n\n==Current programmes==\n*''[[Adventure Time]]'' (Hora de Aventuras)\n*''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]'' (El asombroso mundo de Gumball)\n*''[[Apple & Onion]]'' (Manzana y Cebolleta)\n*''[[Bakugan: Battle Planet]]''\n*''[[Be Cool, Scooby-Doo!]]'' (Enrollate, Scooby-Doo!)\n* [[Ben 10 (2016 TV series)|''Ben 10'' (2016)]]\n*''[[Beyblade Burst]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Bunnicula (TV series)|Bunnicula]]\n*''[[Chowder (TV series)|Chowder]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Clarence (American TV series)|Clarence]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Craig of the Creek]]'' (El Mundo de Craig)\n*''[[Doraemon]]''\n*''[[Dragon Ball Super]]'' \n*''[[Gormiti (2018 TV series)|Gormiti]]''\n*''[[Grizzy and the Lemmings]]''\n*''[[The Happos Family]]'' \n*''[[Johnny Test]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Lego Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]''\n*''[[Mao Mao: Heroes of Pure Heart]]'' (Mao Mao)\n*''[[Mighty Magiswords]]'' (Poderosas Magiespadas)\n*''[[Idol x Warrior Miracle Tunes!|Miracle Tunes]]''\n*''[[Mr. Bean: The Animated Series]]'' (Mr Bean)\n*''[[My Knight and Me]]'' (Mi Caballero y Yo)\n*''[[Nexo Knights]]\n*''[[New Looney Tunes]]\n*''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]''\n*''[[Looney Tunes]]\n*''[[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|The Powerpuff Girls]]'' (Las Supernenas)\n*''[[Pet Pals]]'' (Mascotas)\n*''[[Regular Show]]'' (Historias corrientes) (replays)\n*''[[Steven Universe]]''\n*''[[Summer Camp Island]]'' (Campamento Magico)\n*''[[Teen Titans Go! (TV series)|Teen Titans Go!]]''\n*''[[The Tom and Jerry Show (2014 TV series)|The Tom and Jerry Show (2014)]] (El Show de Tom y Jerry)\n*''[[Toony Tube]]''\n*''[[Uncle Grandpa]]'' (Tito Yayo) (replays)\n*''[[Unikitty!]]\n*''[[We Bare Bears]]'' (Somos osos)\n\n==Former programmes==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[A Penguin's Troubles]]''\n*''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]''\n*''[[The Adventures of Chuck and Friends]]''\n*''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n*''[[The Amazing Spiez!]]''\n*''[[Angel's Friends]]''\n*''[[Animaniacs]]''\n*''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]''\n*''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]''\n*''[[Bakugan: New Vestroia]]''\n*''[[Bakugan: Gundalian Invaders]]''\n*''[[Barbie: Life in the Dreamhouse]]''\n*''[[Batman]]''\n*''[[Ben 10 (2005 TV series)|Ben 10 (2005)]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Challenge]]''\n*''[[Beyblade Metal Fury]]''\n*''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]''\n*''[[Beyblade: Metal Masters]]''\n*''[[Bratz (TV series)|Bratz]]''\n*''[[Camp Lazlo]]''\n*''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]''\n*''[[Code Lyoko]]''\n*''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]''\n*''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]''\n*''[[Cow and Chicken]]''\n*''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]''\n*''[[Digimon (anime)|Digimon]]''\n*''[[Dinosaur King]]''\n*''[[Doctor Who]]''\n*''[[Dragon Ball Z]]''\n*''[[DreamWorks Dragons]] Riders of Berk''\n*''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]''\n*''[[Ed, Edd'n Eddy]]''\n*''[[Ever After High]]''\n*''[[Family Game Night (TV series)|Family Game Night]]''\n*''[[Foster's Home for Imaginary Friends]]''\n*''[[Garfield and Friends]]''\n*''[[The Garfield Show]]''\n*''[[Generator Rex]]''\n*''[[Geronimo Stilton (TV series)|Geronimo Stilton]]''\n*''[[Gormiti Nature Unleashed]]''\n*''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]''\n*''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi]]''\n*''[[The Heroic Quest of the Valiant Prince Ivandoe]]''\n*''[[Inspector Gadget (2015 TV series)|Inspector Gadget]]''\n*''[[Inazuma Eleven (anime)|Inazuma Eleven]]''\n*''[[Jewelpet (anime)|Jewelpet]]''\n*''[[Jewelpet Twinkle]]''\n*''[[Johnny Bravo]]''\n*''[[La Voz (Spanish TV series)|La Voz Kidz]]''\n*''[[LazyTown]]''\n*''[[Lego Star Wars: The Padawan Menace]]''\n*''[[Lego Star Wars: The Yoda Chronicles]]''\n*''[[Level Up (U.S. TV series)|Level Up]]''\n*''[[The Life and Times of Juniper Lee]]''\n*''[[Life with Derek]]''\n*''[[Life with Boys]]''\n*''[[Looney Tunes]]''\n*''[[Malcolm in the Middle]]''\n*''[[Masha and the Bear]]''\n*''[[Martin Mystery]]''\n*''[[The Marvelous Misadventures of Flapjack]]''\n*''[[Mike, Lu & Og]]''\n*''[[Mixels]]''\n*''[[Monster High]]''\n*''[[Mucha Lucha]]''\n*''[[My Gym Partner's a Monkey]]''\n*''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]''\n*''[[Naruto]]''\n*''[[Naruto Shippuden]]''\n*''[[Oggy and the Cockroaches]]''\n*''[[One Piece]]''\n*''[[Out of Jimmy's Head]]''\n*''[[Over the Garden Wall (miniseries)|Over the Garden Wall]]''\n*''[[The Pink Panther (1993 TV series)]]''\n*''[[Polly Pocket#TV series|Polly Pocket]]''\n*''[[Pound Puppies (2010 TV series)|Pound Puppies]]''\n*''[[Power Rangers Samurai]]''\n*''[[Power Rangers Megaforce]]''\n*''[[The Powerpuff Girls]] (1998)''\n*''[[Powerpuff Girls Z]]''\n*''[[Primeval (TV series)|Primeval]]''\n*''[[Ranma \u00bd]]''\n*''[[Sally Bollywood]]''\n*''[[The Secret Saturdays]]''\n*''[[The Smurfs (TV series)|The Smurfs]]''\n*''[[Sonic X]]''\n*''[[The Sylvester and Tweety Mysteries]]''\n*''[[Taz-Mania]]''\n*''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]''\n*''[[Thomas and Friends]]''\n*''[[Tiny Toon Adventures]]''\n*''[[Titeuf]]''\n*''[[Tom and Jerry]]''\n*''[[Top Cat]]''\n*''[[Transformers Animated]]''\n*''[[Transformers: Prime]]''\n*''[[Unnatural History (TV series)|Unnatural History]]''\n*''[[Wacky Races (1968 TV series)|Wacky Races]]''\n*''[[Wakfu (TV series)|Wakfu]]''\n*''[[Wallace and Gromit's Cracking Contraptions]]''\n*''[[What's New, Scooby-Doo?]]''\n*''[[Wipeout (2008 U.S. game show)|Wipeout]]''\n*''[[Xiaolin Showdown]]''\n*''[[Yo Gabba Gabba]]''\n*''[[Yo-Kai Watch]]''\n*''[[Yogi Bear]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Boing (France)]]\n* [[Boing (Italy)]]\n* [[Boing (Africa)]]\n* [[Cartoon Network (Spain)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.boing.es}} {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.cartoonnetwork.es Cartoon Network (former channel)] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Telecinco}}\n{{Mediaset}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{Spanish television stations}}\n\n[[Category:Television stations in Spain]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Turner Broadcasting System Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Children's television networks]]\n[[Category:Channels of Mediaset Espa\u00f1a Comunicaci\u00f3n]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox TV channel\n| name              = Boing\n| logofile          = Boing.svg\n| logosize          = 150px\n| launch            = {{Start date and age|df=y|2010|9|1}}\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    = [[576i]] ([[16:9]] [[Standard-definition television|SDTV]])\n| network           = [[Telecinco]]\n| owner             = [[Warner Bros]]. Espa\u00f1a (50%)<br />[[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] (50%)\n| founder           = [[Gestevisi\u00f3n Telecinco]]\n| slogan            = ''\u00a1Juntos, mejor!'' (English: ''Better together!'')\n| country           = Spain\n| language          = Spanish \n| broadcast area    = Spain (via terrestrial)\n| headquarters      = \n| web               = [http://www.boing.es/ www.boing.es]\n| sat serv 1        = \n| sat chan 1        = \n| cable serv 1      = \n| cable chan 1      = \n| iptv serv 1       = \n| iptv chan 1       = \n| sister names      = Mediaset Espa\u00f1a:<br />[[Telecinco]]<br />[[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]]<br />[[Divinity (TV channel)|Divinity]]<br />[[Energy (TV channel)|Energy]]<br />[[Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n]]<br />Turner Broadcasting System Europe:<br />[[Cartoon Network (Portugal)|Cartoon Network Portugal]]<br />[[Boomerang (Portugal)|Boomerang Portugal]]<br />[[TNT (Spain)|TNT]]<br />[[Turner Classic Movies (Spain)|TCM]]<br />[[CNN International]]<br />WarnerMedia Entertainment:<br />[[HBO (International)#Spain|HBO Espa\u00f1a]]\n}}\n'''Boing''' is a Spanish free-to-air television channel, owned by a joint venture between [[Mediaset Espa\u00f1a]] and [[Warner Bros.]] through its Spain unit, which was launched in 2010. When [[Cartoonito (Spain)|Cartoonito]] and [[Cartoon Network (Spain)|Cartoon Network]] were shut down on 30 June 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.es/|title=Former Channel|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150327012201/http://www.cartoonnetwork.es/|archivedate=27 March 2015}}</ref> many Cartoon Network programmes were moved to Boing, alongside new Boomerang programmes. The shows on the channel are also available in English via a second audio feed, whereas Doraemon uses the original Japanese audio track.\n\nAdditional Boing feeds are available in [[Boing (Italy)|Italy]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boingtv.it/|title=Boing Italy}}</ref> [[Boing (France)|France]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boingtv.fr/|title=Boing France}}</ref> and [[Boing (Africa)|Sub-Saharan Africa]], with Cartoon Network and Boomerang also being available in those territories.\n\n==History==\nOn 28 November 2008, Telecinco and Turner<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/1,20081128,9580,1.html</ref>, reached an agreement to introduce a children's programming block on the Telecinco channel, with some 42 hours of weekly programming. Three days later, the Boing drawing container began in [[Telecinco]] and [[Telecinco 2]].\n\nMonths later, on 11 May 2009, Boing went from Telecinco 2 to [[Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n]], of the same group, with the same contents and similar schedules, since Telecinco 2 became [[La Siete]] and changed part of its programming.\n\nOn 2 August 2010, Telecinco announced the launch of Boing as its fourth free-to-air television channel,<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/15944/telecinco-lanza-boing-cuarto-canal-adios-lanueve/</ref> moving from a series container to an open-themed channel dedicated 24 hours a day to the youngest in the house, with Turner star products. In its first weeks of broadcasting, Boing offered a six-hour programming loop that hosted the animations ''[[Geronimo Stilton]]'', ''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]'', ''[[Dinosaur King]]'', ''[[Powerpuff Girls Z]]'', ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]'', ''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]'' and ''[[Inazuma Eleven]]'',<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/16098/boing-inicia-emisiones-proximo-1-septiembre/</ref> to incorporate progressively own content in the following weeks in a grid in which, since then, fictions aimed at children and adolescent viewers coexist.\n\nOn 9 August 2010, it began its test broadcasts showing a letter of adjustment and on 23 August a promotional loop of series that would be broadcast in its premiere on 1 September of the same year.<ref>http://www.mundoplus.tv/noticias/?seccion=tv_digital&id=8090</ref>\n\nOn 1 September 2010, its official broadcasts began with a programme that included a welcome selection of the Turner factory's star products.<ref>http://www.mundoplus.tv/noticias/?seccion=tv_digital&id=8106</ref> Telecinco's new children's channel premiered with a 0.58% quota. With the arrival of the new channel, ''Boing'', the series container of Telecinco and Factor\u00eda de Ficci\u00f3n was renamed ''[[SuperBoing]]'', although on 1 January 2011, it ceased broadcasting on both channels after the merger with [[Cuatro (TV channel)|Cuatro]], and its contents were shown exclusively on the Boing channel.\n\nOn 28 November 2010 the channel premiered ''[[Ed, Edd n Eddy's Big Picture Show|La gran pel\u00edcula de Ed, Edd y Eddy]]'', an animated film from the series [[Ed, Edd and Eddy]]. Although its official release was one year and 22 days earlier (6 November 2009) on the private and pay-TV network [[Cartoon Network (Spain)|Cartoon Network]], it was the first film broadcast on Boing and the first feature of a previous series broadcast on the network.\n\nOn 31 May 2011, the cable operator [[ONO (Spain)|ONO]] incorporated the Boing channel in its basic package (which already has 17 children's channels) on dial 64, so all subscribers to the operator have access to that channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/19778/boing-divinity-incorporan-oferta-ono/</ref><ref>http://satcesc.com/web/2011/05/25/la-television-de-ono-incopora-los-canales-divinity-y-boing/</ref>\n\nOn 20 June 2011, Boing's creative and advertising group, [[Time Warner]] and [[Publiespa\u00f1a]], changed the channel's corporate image with new advertising blocks, adding animated curtains in the presentation of the series and more information. The logo was also modified to a darker tone and with a spherical shape.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110628220729/http://tecnoociencia.com/2011/06/26/boing-cambia-su-imagen-corporativa-y-su-mosca/</ref>\n\nOn 28 June 2011, [[Mediaset Spain]] announced that, from the fourth quarter of the year, Publiespa\u00f1a would launch a commercial policy in the channel with ''Desayuna y merienda con Boing'' containers. Both are presented by the EVA robot.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/20275/robot-eva-presentara-desayuna-con-boing-merienda-con-boing/</ref>\n\nOn 16 August 2011, pay-TV operator [[Movistar TV]] added the Boing channel on its 63 dial. It later changed to 69 dial. In 2015 it became Movistar+, so it is now on 97 dial.\n\nOn 7 September 2011, Boing's official website renewed the content of the website, transforming it to its new corporate image and creating new sections. These sections include a games section, a series section, a video and photo portal and a blog where users are informed daily of the new releases that come to the channel.<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20120114233421/http://www.boing.es/blog/boinges-%C2%A1una-nueva-web-para-empezar-bien-el-curso</ref>\n\nOn 16 September 2011, Grupo Zeta launched the first issue of Boing Magazine to the kiosks. After an agreement between Grupo Zeta and the communication groups Turner Broadcasting System and Mediaset Espa\u00f1a, the publication was born with the same drive as the young children's channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/21265/sale-mercado-revista-boing/</ref>\n\nOn Saturday, 4 February 2012, Mediaset Spain's children's channel reached its daily audience record with a 1.8% screen share, and was even one tenth (1.9%) away from [[Neox]], [[Atresmedia]]'s thematic channel.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/audiencias/2012-02-04/</ref> One month after making history, on 3 March of the same year, it obtained a 2% screen share, two tenths away from its main competitor Disney Channel (2.2%).<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/23921/peppa-pig-cuela-mas-vistos-dia-gran-112-clan/</ref> Finally, weeks after reaching the daily maximum with a quota of 2.0%, on Saturday 14 April it repeated its success by giving the channel an audience share of 2.5% of the screen in total day and reaching the historic maximum since its premiere.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/24505/fdf-lidera-prime-time-cadenas-tematicas-tdt-la-que-se-avecina/</ref> Almost two months later, on 2 June, the children's channel of Mediaset Spain broke a new record on Saturday, giving the group a quota of 2.6% daily screen share.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/25289/phineas-y-ferb-arrasa-manana-disney-channel-impresionante-10/</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, Boing achieved the monthly maximum in DTT with a share of 2.1%, surpassing its great competitor [[Disney Channel (Spain)|Disney Channel]] by 3 tenths.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/26192/audiencias-maximo-mayoria-cadenas-tdt-mediaset-fdf-boing-divinity-energy/</ref> The channel gets the best result of its history thanks to films such as ''[[Ice Age]]''. In terms of audience, it is the second most watched channel among children from 4 to 12 years with a commercial target of 14.1%.\n\nSince November 2015, one month after being awarded a new HD channel by the government, Mediaset broadcast Boing in HD on a temporary basis until 7 January 2016<ref>http://perdidosenlatele.com/2015/11/28/mediaset-adjudica-a-boing-su-nueva-licencia-en-hd/</ref> Being replaced by [[Energy HD]], and this was replaced on 21 April]by [[Be Mad TV]], the new channel of Mediaset Spain.<ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/52400/mediaset-espana-boing-hd-energy-hd-espera-lanzar-nuevo-canal/</ref><ref>http://www.formulatv.com/noticias/55140/be-mad-tv-puesto-fecha-inicio-emisiones/</ref><ref>http://www.adslzone.tv/2016/03/18/be-mad-tv-sera-el-nombre-del-nuevo-canal-de-mediaset/</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2016, the channel renewed its corporate image, adapting to the worldwide image of the channel that premiered its [[Boing (Italy)|Italian version]] on 7 March of the same year.\n\n==Current programmes==\n*''[[Adventure Time]]'' (Hora de Aventuras)\n*''[[The Amazing World of Gumball]]'' (El asombroso mundo de Gumball)\n*''[[Apple & Onion]]'' (Manzana y Cebolleta)\n*''[[Bakugan: Battle Planet]]''\n*''[[Be Cool, Scooby-Doo!]]'' (Enrollate, Scooby-Doo!)\n* [[Ben 10 (2016 TV series)|''Ben 10'' (2016)]]\n*''[[Beyblade Burst]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Bunnicula (TV series)|Bunnicula]]\n*''[[Chowder (TV series)|Chowder]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Clarence (American TV series)|Clarence]]'' (replays)\n*''[[Craig of the Creek]]'' (El Mundo de Craig)\n*''[[Doraemon]]''\n*''[[Dragon Ball Super]]'' \n*''[[Gormiti (2018 TV series)|Gormiti]]''\n*''[[Grizzy and the Lemmings]]''\n*''[[The Happos Family]]'' \n*''[[Lego Ninjago: Masters of Spinjitzu]]''\n*''[[Mighty Magiswords]]'' (Poderosas Magiespadas)\n*''[[Idol x Warrior Miracle Tunes!|Miracle Tunes]]''\n*''[[Mr. Bean: The Animated Series]]'' (Mr Bean)\n*''[[My Knight and Me]]'' (Mi Caballero y Yo)\n*''[[Nexo Knights]]\n*''[[New Looney Tunes]]\n*''[[OK K.O.! Let's Be Heroes]]''\n*''[[Looney Tunes]]\n*''[[The Powerpuff Girls (2016 TV series)|The Powerpuff Girls]]'' (Las Supernenas)\n*''[[Pet Pals]]'' (Mascotas)\n*''[[Regular Show]]'' (Historias corrientes) (replays)\n*''[[Steven Universe]]''\n*''[[Summer Camp Island]]'' (Campamento Magico)\n*''[[Teen Titans Go! (TV series)|Teen Titans Go!]]''\n*''[[The Tom and Jerry Show (2014 TV series)|The Tom and Jerry Show (2014)]] (El Show de Tom y Jerry)\n*''[[Toony Tube]]''\n*''[[Uncle Grandpa]]'' (Tito Yayo) (replays)\n*''[[Unikitty!]]\n*''[[We Bare Bears]]'' (Somos osos)\n\n==Former programmes==\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n*''[[A Penguin's Troubles]]''\n*''[[A Pup Named Scooby-Doo]]''\n*''[[The Adventures of Chuck and Friends]]''\n*''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]''\n*''[[The Amazing Spiez!]]''\n*''[[Angel's Friends]]''\n*''[[Animaniacs]]''\n*''[[The Avengers: Earth's Mightiest Heroes]]''\n*''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]''\n*''[[Bakugan: New Vestroia]]''\n*''[[Bakugan: Gundalian Invaders]]''\n*''[[Barbie: Life in the Dreamhouse]]''\n*''[[Batman]]''\n*''[[Ben 10 (2005 TV series)|Ben 10 (2005)]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Alien]]''\n*''[[Ben 10: Ultimate Challenge]]''\n*''[[Beyblade Metal Fury]]''\n*''[[Beyblade: Metal Fusion]]''\n*''[[Beyblade: Metal Masters]]''\n*''[[Bratz (TV series)|Bratz]]''\n*''[[Camp Lazlo]]''\n*''[[Casi \u00c1ngeles]]''\n*''[[Code Lyoko]]''\n*''[[Codename: Kids Next Door]]''\n*''[[Courage the Cowardly Dog]]''\n*''[[Cow and Chicken]]''\n*''[[Dexter's Laboratory]]''\n*''[[Digimon (anime)|Digimon]]''\n*''[[Dinosaur King]]''\n*''[[Doctor Who]]''\n*''[[Dragon Ball Z]]''\n*''[[DreamWorks Dragons]] Riders of Berk''\n*''[[Duck Dodgers (TV series)|Duck Dodgers]]''\n*''[[Ed, Edd'n Eddy]]''\n*''[[Ever After High]]''\n*''[[Family Game Night (TV series)|Family Game Night]]''\n*''[[Foster's Home for Imaginary Friends]]''\n*''[[Garfield and Friends]]''\n*''[[The Garfield Show]]''\n*''[[Generator Rex]]''\n*''[[Geronimo Stilton (TV series)|Geronimo Stilton]]''\n*''[[Gormiti Nature Unleashed]]''\n*''[[The Grim Adventures of Billy & Mandy]]''\n*''[[Hi Hi Puffy AmiYumi]]''\n*''[[The Heroic Quest of the Valiant Prince Ivandoe]]''\n*''[[Inspector Gadget (2015 TV series)|Inspector Gadget]]''\n*''[[Inazuma Eleven (anime)|Inazuma Eleven]]''\n*''[[Jewelpet (anime)|Jewelpet]]''\n*''[[Jewelpet Twinkle]]''\n*''[[Johnny Bravo]]''\n*''[[Johnny Test]]''\n*''[[La Voz (Spanish TV series)|La Voz Kidz]]''\n*''[[LazyTown]]''\n*''[[Lego Star 