ces==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|www.boing.es}} {{in lang|es}}\n*[http://www.cartoonnetwork.es Cartoon Network (former channel)] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Telecinco}}\n{{Mediaset}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{Spanish television stations}}\n\n[[Category:Television stations in Spain]]\n[[Category:Television channels and stations established in 2010]]\n[[Category:Turner Broadcasting System Spain]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language television stations]]\n[[Category:Children's television networks]]\n[[Category:Channels of Mediaset Espa\u00f1a Comunicaci\u00f3n]]\n", "name_user": "Shane6456", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boing_(Spanish_TV_channel)"}
{"title_page": "Panoptica", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP one source|date=June 2019}}\n{{External links|date=January 2019}}\n{{Notability|music|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Roberto A. Mendoza (Panoptica)\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = \n| genre               = electronic\n| years_active        = Late 1980 &ndash; present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = \n}}\n'''Roberto A. Mendoza ''', known as '''Panoptica''', has been one of the figures in the [[Mexico|Mexican]] electronic scene since the late 80s, founding bands like electro pos-industrial outfit [[Artefakto]] and in the late 1990s being part of the Tijuana-based norte\u00f1a-meets-techno [[Nortec Collective]]. He has also been releasing tracks as Pan\u00f3ptica and it was under this name that English DJ [[John Peel]] took notice, inviting him to do one of his Peel sessions for the [[BBC]] in 2001. In 2005 Roberto had embarked on finishing two projects, one called \"Desierto\" and the other \"Mendoza\", where friends like [[David J]]. ([[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], [[Love and Rockets (band)|Love and Rockets]]) lend a hand on bass and guitars. In late 2007 he separated from the Nortec Collective and created the \"Nortec Panoptica Orchestra\" a band for his live shows. In early 2008 Roberto decided to record a new solo album to push and further develop the electronic sound, working independently from the Tijuana collective and with new musical partners Zoell Farrujia (Ambiente), Benjamin Rivera (Grupo de Acero), Edgar Hernandez (Banda Aguacaliente), Adrian Rodriguez (Ko\u00f1orte\u00f1o), and special guests: Javiera Mena, Khan Oral, Yerba Buena. The album was set to be released in March 2010 in Vinyl LP and digital form\n\n== External links ==\n{{discogs artist|artist=Panoptica}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican electronic music]]\n[[Category:Mexican electronic musicians]]\n\n{{electronic-musician-stub}}\n{{mexico-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP one source|date=June 2019}}\n{{External links|date=January 2019}}\n{{Notability|music|date=January 2019}}\n}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Roberto A. Mendoza (Panoptica)\n| image               =\n| caption             = \n| image_size          = \n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               = \n| origin              = \n| genre               = electronic\n| years_active        = Late 1980 &ndash; present\n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = \n| website             = \n| current_members     = \n| past_members        = \n}}\n'''Roberto A. Mendoza ''', known as '''Panoptica''', has been one of the figures in the [[Mexico|Mexican]] electronic scene since the late 80s, founding bands like electro pos-industrial outfit [[Artefakto]] and in the late 90\u2019s being part of the Tijuana-based norte\u00f1a-meets-techno [[Nortec Collective]]. He has also been releasing tracks as Pan\u00f3ptica and it was under this name that English DJ [[John Peel]] took notice, inviting him to do one of his Peel sessions for the [[BBC]] in 2001. In 2005 Roberto had embarked on finishing two projects, one called \"Desierto\" and the other \"Mendoza\", where friends like [[David J]]. ([[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]], [[Love and Rockets (band)|Love and Rockets]]) lend a hand on bass and guitars. In late 2007 he separated from the Nortec Collective and created the \"Nortec Panoptica Orchestra\" a band for his live shows. In early 2008 Roberto decided to record a new solo album to push and further develop the electronic sound, working independently from the Tijuana collective and with new musical partners Zoell Farrujia (Ambiente), Benjamin Rivera (Grupo de Acero), Edgar Hernandez (Banda Aguacaliente), Adrian Rodriguez (Ko\u00f1orte\u00f1o), and special guests: Javiera Mena, Khan Oral, Yerba Buena. The album was set to be released in March 2010 in Vinyl LP and digital form\n\n== External links ==\n{{discogs artist|artist=Panoptica}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican electronic music]]\n[[Category:Mexican electronic musicians]]\n\n{{electronic-musician-stub}}\n{{mexico-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panoptica"}
{"title_page": "Parragon", "text_new": "{{Infobox publisher\n| name         =Parragon Books \n| image        = \n| caption      =\n| parent       = [[D. C. Thomson & Co.]]\n| status       = Defunct\n| traded_as    =\n| predecessor  =\n| founded      = 1988\n| founder      = Guy Parr and Paul Anderson\n| successor    = \n| country      = [[United Kingdom]]\n| headquarters = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[England]]\n| distribution = Europe, North America, Asia, Australia<ref>{{Cite web| title = Contact Us| work = Parragon US| accessdate = 2017-11-12| url = https://www.parragon.com/contact-us/}}</ref>\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Books\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| numemployees =\n| url          = {{URL|http://www.parragon.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Parragon Books Ltd''', a [[United Kingdom]] publishing company, was formed in 1988 by friends Guy Parr and Paul Anderson. In 2001, it became part of [[D. C. Thomson & Co.]]\n\n==History==\n\nParragon began its early years by developing business through overstocks and reprinting dormant titles from key publishers archives such as [[Penguin Books]] and [[HarperCollins]].\n\nIn 1992, Parragon shifted focus through a trial bargain book table placed in [[Asda]]'s grocery store in [[Nuneaton]]. Following the trial's success, Parragon extended their bargain book strategy to other key retailers such as [[Tesco]] and [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]]. As sales increased, these retailers employed Parragon to distribute titles from other major publishers. The distribution business continued until the mid to late 1990s before Parragon decided to concentrate on their own publishing. The distribution business was offloaded to Cork International, who continued to service the grocers until 2004 before their demise.\n\nIn the late 1990s, Parragon's publishing business increased, and the company opened new offices in New York and Cologne before [[DC Thomson]] took a controlling stake in 2001. Their acquisition of Funtastic gave them significant distribution into the Australian market before further sales offices were opened in India and China, bringing the Parragon brand global.\n\nIn 2005, Parragon signed a deal with [[Disney]] to publish books into the UK book trade, hiring new staff to oversee the Disney brand license.<ref name=\"bookseller\" /> Significant licensing activity, including brands such as [[Looney Tunes]] and [[Bratz]] followed. Parragon also expanded focus across the children's, adult reference, and cooking categories.\n\nIn 2007, Parragon launched its global cookbook imprint, 'Love Food'. Parragon has sold over 100 million Love Food books worldwide. Core series include Step by Step, 100 Best Recipes, Food Heroes as well as stand alone titles. \n\nIn 2011 Parragon renewed their existing license with [[Discovery Kids]] which included rights to publish titles in eBook format. Parragon later signed a deal for a new series of activity and novelty books for the 'Squinkies' toy brand,<ref name=\"pw\" />and a new license for a range of books based on the [[Power Rangers Samurai]] brand.<ref name=\"kidscreen\" />\n\nIn 2012 Parragon launched its stationery imprint, Life Canvas. In February 2013, the Giftware Association 'Highly Commended' the Life Canvas 'Story of Me and My...' range of keepsake journals in the finals of the 2013 Gift of the Year Awards. Later in August 2013, Life Canvas was awarded 3 awards at the 2013 UK Stationery Awards including the 'Special Judges Award'.  In 2014, Parragon published two Life Canvas collections called 'Wild' and 'Paris'.\n\nIn May 2012, Nickelodeon, Viacom Consumer Products and Parragon announced Parragon's acquisition of master publishing rights for the Nickelodeon entertainment brand portfolio.  \n\nIn 2013, Parragon announced a licensing partnership with Mattel for publishing rights to their Monster High brand in the UK, North America and Germany. In 2014 Parragon acquired publishing rights for Mattel brand 'Ever After High'.\n\nIn 2018, Parragon announced its closure. Cottage Door Press acquired the US and UK rights of the company.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Cottage Door Press to Acquire Parragon Assets| work = PublishersWeekly.com| accessdate = 2018-12-08| url = https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/76512-cottage-door-press-to-acquire-parragon-assets.html}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"bookseller\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/parragon-poaches-hc-pair-disney.html|title=Parragon Poaches HC Pair For Disney}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"pw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/47626-parragon-renews-discovery-kids-deal-adds-e-books-.html|title=Parragon Renews Discovery Kids Deal, Adds EBooks}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"kidscreen\">{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2011/07/04/power-rangers-samurai-gets-book-deal/|title=Power Rangers Samurai Gets Book Deal}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.parragon.com}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n{{DCThomson}}\n\n[[Category:Book publishing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bath, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1988]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox publisher\n| name         =Parragon Books \n| image        = \n| caption      =\n| parent       = [[D. C. Thomson & Co.]]\n| status       = Defunct\n| traded_as    =\n| predecessor  =\n| founded      = 1988\n| founder      = Guy Parr and Paul Anderson\n| successor    = \n| country      = [[United Kingdom]]\n| headquarters = [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[England]]\n| distribution = Europe, North America, Asia, Australia<ref>{{Cite web| title = Contact Us| work = Parragon US| accessdate = 2017-11-12| url = https://www.parragon.com/contact-us/}}</ref>\n| keypeople    = \n| publications = Books\n| topics       = \n| genre        = \n| imprints     = \n| revenue      = \n| numemployees =\n| url          = {{URL|http://www.parragon.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Parragon Books Ltd''', a [[United Kingdom]] publishing company, was formed in 1988 by friends Guy Parr and Paul Anderson. In 2001, it became part of [[D. C. Thomson & Co.]]\n\n==History==\n\nParragon began its early years by developing business through overstocks and reprinting dormant titles from key publishers archives such as [[Penguin Books]] and [[HarperCollins]].\n\nIn 1992, Parragon shifted focus through a trial bargain book table placed in [[Asda]]'s grocery store in [[Nuneaton]]. Following the trial's success, Parragon extended their bargain book strategy to other key retailers such as [[Tesco]] and [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]]. As sales increased, these retailers employed Parragon to distribute titles from other major publishers. The distribution business continued until the mid to late 90's before Parragon decided to concentrate on their own publishing. The distribution business was offloaded to Cork International, who continued to service the grocers until 2004 before their demise.\n\nIn the late 1990s, Parragon's publishing business increased, and the company opened new offices in New York and Cologne before [[DC Thomson]] took a controlling stake in 2001. Their acquisition of Funtastic gave them significant distribution into the Australian market before further sales offices were opened in India and China, bringing the Parragon brand global.\n\nIn 2005, Parragon signed a deal with [[Disney]] to publish books into the UK book trade, hiring new staff to oversee the Disney brand license.<ref name=\"bookseller\" /> Significant licensing activity, including brands such as [[Looney Tunes]] and [[Bratz]] followed. Parragon also expanded focus across the children's, adult reference, and cooking categories.\n\nIn 2007, Parragon launched its global cookbook imprint, 'Love Food'. Parragon has sold over 100 million Love Food books worldwide. Core series include Step by Step, 100 Best Recipes, Food Heroes as well as stand alone titles. \n\nIn 2011 Parragon renewed their existing license with [[Discovery Kids]] which included rights to publish titles in eBook format. Parragon later signed a deal for a new series of activity and novelty books for the 'Squinkies' toy brand,<ref name=\"pw\" />and a new license for a range of books based on the [[Power Rangers Samurai]] brand.<ref name=\"kidscreen\" />\n\nIn 2012 Parragon launched its stationery imprint, Life Canvas. In February 2013, the Giftware Association 'Highly Commended' the Life Canvas 'Story of Me and My...' range of keepsake journals in the finals of the 2013 Gift of the Year Awards. Later in August 2013, Life Canvas was awarded 3 awards at the 2013 UK Stationery Awards including the 'Special Judges Award'.  In 2014, Parragon published two Life Canvas collections called 'Wild' and 'Paris'.\n\nIn May 2012, Nickelodeon, Viacom Consumer Products and Parragon announced Parragon's acquisition of master publishing rights for the Nickelodeon entertainment brand portfolio.  \n\nIn 2013, Parragon announced a licensing partnership with Mattel for publishing rights to their Monster High brand in the UK, North America and Germany. In 2014 Parragon acquired publishing rights for Mattel brand 'Ever After High'.\n\nIn 2018, Parragon announced its closure. Cottage Door Press acquired the US and UK rights of the company.<ref>{{Cite web| title = Cottage Door Press to Acquire Parragon Assets| work = PublishersWeekly.com| accessdate = 2018-12-08| url = https://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/industry-news/publisher-news/article/76512-cottage-door-press-to-acquire-parragon-assets.html}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"bookseller\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/parragon-poaches-hc-pair-disney.html|title=Parragon Poaches HC Pair For Disney}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"pw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/pw/by-topic/childrens/childrens-industry-news/article/47626-parragon-renews-discovery-kids-deal-adds-e-books-.html|title=Parragon Renews Discovery Kids Deal, Adds EBooks}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"kidscreen\">{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2011/07/04/power-rangers-samurai-gets-book-deal/|title=Power Rangers Samurai Gets Book Deal}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.parragon.com}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n{{DCThomson}}\n\n[[Category:Book publishing companies of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Bath, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Publishing companies established in 1988]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo/fmt (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parragon"}
{"title_page": "Saint Stephen", "text_new": "{{about|Deacon Stephen, a martyred saint|the first king of Hungary|Stephen I of Hungary|other uses|St. Stephen (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1st-century early Christian martyr and saint}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name         = Saint Stephen\n|image        = Polittico del 1476, s. stefano.jpg\n|imagesize    = 200px\n|caption      = ''Saint Stephan'' by [[Carlo Crivelli]]\n|titles       = [[Deacon]] <br>Protomartyr of The Faith\n|birth_date   = AD 5\n|death_date= AD 33-37 (aged 28-32)\n|death_place  = [[Jerusalem]], [[Judaea]], [[Roman Empire]]\n|feast_day    = 25 December ([[Armenian Christianity]])<br>26 December (Western)<br>27 December (Eastern)<br>Tobi 1 ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Christianity]])\n|canonized_date= [[Pre-Congregation]]\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|major_shrine=\n|attributes   = [[Christian martyrs#Degrees of martyrdom|Red Martyr]], stones, [[dalmatic]], [[censer]], miniature church, [[Gospel Book]], [[martyr's palm]]. In [[Eastern Christianity]] he often wears an [[orarion]]\n|patronage    = [[Altar server|Altar Servers]] [http://totus2us.com/vocation/saints/st-stephen/];[[Acoma Pueblo|Acoma]] Indian [[Pueblo]]; [[casket]] makers; [[Cetona|Cetona, Italy]]; [[deacons]]; [[headache]]s; [[horse]]s; [[Kessel, Belgium]]; [[masonry|masons]]; [[Owensboro, Kentucky]]; [[Passau|Passau, Germany]]; [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]]; [[Dodoma]], [[Tanzania]]; [[Serbia]]; [[Republic of Srpska]]; [[Prato|Prato, Italy]] [http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-stephen-the-martyr/]\n|issues=\n|suppressed_date=\n|venerated_in = [[Roman Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Catholic Church]]es<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]]<br/>[[Oriental Orthodox Church]]es<br/>[[Assyrian Church of the East]]<br/>[[Anglican Communion]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen''' ({{lang-grc-gre|\u03a3\u03c4\u03ad\u03c6\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2}} ''St\u00e9phanos'', meaning \"wreath, crown\" and by extension \"reward, honor\", often given as a title rather than as a name, {{lang-he|\u05e1\u05d8\u05e4\u05e0\u05d5\u05e1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05d3\u05d5\u05e9}}), (c. AD 5 \u2013 c. AD 34) traditionally venerated as the [[protomartyr]] or first martyr of [[Christianity]],<ref name=ssdca>[http://www.ssdca.org/ssdca/index.cfm/st-stephen-bio/ \"St. Stephen the Deacon\"], St. Stephen Diaconal Community Association, Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester.</ref> was according to the [[Acts of the Apostles]] a [[deacon]] in the early church at [[Jerusalem]] who aroused the enmity of members of various [[synagogue]]s by his teachings. Accused of [[blasphemy]] at his trial, he made a speech denouncing the Jewish authorities who were sitting in judgment on him and was then [[stoned to death]]. His [[martyrdom]] was witnessed by [[Saul of Tarsus]], a [[Pharisee]] who would later become a follower of Jesus and known as [[Paul the Apostle]].\n\nThe only primary source for information about Stephen is the [[New Testament]] book of the Acts of the Apostles.<ref name=\"Newadvent\">{{cite web |url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/14286b.htm |title=Saint Stephen \n|author=Souvay, Charles|date= |work=Catholic Encyclopedia,1912 |publisher=New Advent |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>  Stephen is mentioned in [[Acts 6]] as one of the Greek-speaking [[Hellenistic Jew]]s selected to participate in a fairer distribution of welfare to the Greek-speaking widows.<ref>Mal Couch, ''A Bible Handbook to the Acts of the Apostles'', 2003, p. 246. \"Stephen is distinguished as \"a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit\" (Acts 6:5). Stephen and the other men were Hellenistic Jews whose native language was Greek. He had lived with Gentiles in other parts of the Roman Empire.\"</ref>\n\nThe [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Anglican]], [[Oriental Orthodox]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]es, and the [[Church of the East]] venerate Stephen as a [[saint]]. The [[Lutheran]] Church recognizes Stephen as a saint as it recognizes all Christians as saints.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1580boc.org/ap/xxi-ix |title=Article XXI (IX) Of the Invocation of the Saints}}</ref> Traditionally, Stephen is invested with a crown of martyrdom; artistic representations often depict him with three stones and the [[Palm branch (symbol)|martyr's palm frond]]. Eastern Christian [[iconography]] shows him as a young, beardless man with a [[tonsure]], wearing a deacon's [[vestments]], and often holding a miniature church building or a [[censer]].\n\n==Martyrdom==\n===Background===\n\nStephen is first mentioned in the [[Acts of the Apostles]] as one of [[seven deacons]] appointed by the [[Apostle]]s to distribute food and charitable aid to poorer members of the community in the early church. According to Orthodox belief, he was the eldest and is therefore called \"archdeacon\".<ref name=oca>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/saints/lives/2015/12/27/103659-protomartyr-and-archdeacon-stephen|title=Protomartyr and Archdeacon Stephen|publisher=}}</ref> As another deacon, Nicholas of Antioch, is specifically stated to have been a convert to [[Judaism]], it may be assumed that Stephen was born Jewish, but nothing more is known about his previous life.<ref name=\"Newadvent\"/> The reason for the appointment of the deacons is stated to have been dissatisfaction among [[Hellenistic]] (that is, Greek-influenced and Greek-speaking) Jews that their widows were being slighted in preference to Hebraic ones in the d . \n And then he saw thanos he thought it was a grape so he ate it. then he was in endgame for a little ans snapped hus  is Greek, it has been assumed that he was one of these Hellenistic Jews. Stephen is stated to have been full of faith and the Holy Spirit and\n to have performed miracles among the people.{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:5, 8}} \n[[File:St stephen.jpg|thumb|upright|''Stoning of Saint Stephen'', altarpiece of San Giorgio Maggiore, Venice, by Jacopo & Domenico [[Tintoretto]]]]\nIt seems to have been among synagogues of Hellenistic Jews that he performed his teachings and \"signs and wonders\" since it is said that he aroused the opposition of the \"[[Synagogue of the Libertines|Synagogue of the Freedmen]]\", and \"of the Cyrenians, and of the Alexandrians, and of them that were of Cilicia and Asia\".{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:9}} Members of these synagogues had challenged Stephen's teachings, but Stephen had bested them in debate. Furious at this humiliation, they suborned false testimony that Stephen had preached blasphemy against [[Moses]] and God. They dragged him to appear before the [[Sanhedrin]], the supreme legal court of Jewish elders, accusing him of preaching against the [[Second Temple|Temple]] and the [[Torah|Mosaic Law]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:9\u201314}} Stephen is said to have been unperturbed, his face looking like \"that of an angel\".<ref name=\"Newadvent\"/>\n\n===Speech to Sanhedrin===\nIn a long speech to the [[Sanhedrin]] comprising almost the whole of [[Acts 7|Acts chapter 7]], Stephen presents his view of the history of [[Israel]]. The God of glory, he says, appeared to [[Abraham]] in [[Mesopotamia]], thus establishing at the beginning of the speech one of its major themes, that God does not dwell only in one particular building (meaning the Temple).<ref name=\"Williams\">David J. Williams (1989), ''Acts (Understanding the Bible Commentary Series)'', Baker Books, Chapter 16, {{ISBN|978-0-8010-4805-0}}.</ref> Stephen recounts the stories of the [[patriarchs]] in some depth, and goes into even more detail in the case of [[Moses]]. God appeared to Moses in the burning bush,{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:30\u201332}} and inspired Moses to lead his people out of Egypt. Nevertheless, the Israelites turned to other gods.{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:39\u201343}} This establishes the second main theme of Stephen's speech, Israel's disobedience to God.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> Stephen faced two accusations: that he had declared that Jesus would destroy the Temple in Jerusalem and that he had changed the customs of Moses. [[Benedict XVI]] stated that St. Stephen appealed to the Jewish scriptures to prove how the laws of Moses were not subverted by Jesus but, instead, were being fulfilled.<ref>Kerr, David. [http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/st.-stephens-death-shows-importance-of-scripture-pope-says/ \"St. Stephen's death shows importance of Scripture, Pope says\"], Catholic News Agency, 2 May 2012.</ref> Stephen denounces his listeners<ref name=\"Williams\" /> as \"stiff-necked\" people who, just as their ancestors had done, resist the Holy Spirit. \"Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute? They even killed those who predicted the coming of the Righteous One. And now you have betrayed and murdered him.\"{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:51\u201353}}\n\n===The stoning of Stephen===\n[[File:Giovanni Battista Lucini - Martyrdom of St. Stephen.JPG|thumb|260px|''Stoning of Saint Stephen'' by [[Giovanni Battista Lucini]]]]\n\nThus castigated, the account is that the crowd could contain their anger no longer.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/MARY/STEPHEN2.HTM\"Lives of Saints\", John J. Crawley & Co., Inc.]</ref> However, Stephen looked up and cried, \"Look! I see heaven open and the [[Son of Man]] standing on the right hand of God!\" He said that the recently executed Jesus was standing by the side of God.<ref name=\"Williams2\">David J. Williams, ''Acts (Understanding the Bible Commentary Series)'', Baker Books 1989, chapter 17, {{ISBN|978-0-8010-4805-0}}</ref>{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:54}} The people from the crowd, who threw the first stones<ref>{{Bibleverse||Deuteronomy|13:9|HE}} and {{Bibleverse||Deuteronomy|17:7|HE}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams2\" /> laid their coats down so as to be able to do this, at the feet of a \"young man named Saul\" (later known as [[Paul the Apostle]]). Stephen prayed that the Lord would receive his spirit and his killers be forgiven, sank to his knees, and \"fell asleep\".{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:58\u201360}} Saul \"approved of their killing him.\"{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:1}} In the aftermath of Stephen's death, the remaining disciples fled to distant lands, many to [[Antioch]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|11:19\u201320}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Unger |first=Merrill F. |authorlink=Merrill Unger |editor-last=Harrison |editor-first=R. K. |year=2006 |origyear=1957 |title=The New Unger's Bible Dictionary |url= |location=Chicago |publisher=Moody Publishers |at=\"Antioch\" |isbn=978-0-8024-9066-7 }}</ref>\n\n====Location of the martyrdom====\nThe exact site of Stephen's stoning is not mentioned in Acts; instead there are two different traditions. One, claimed by noted French archaeologists [[Louis-Hugues Vincent]] (1872\u20131960) and [[F\u00e9lix-Marie Abel]] (1878\u20131953) to be [[Ancient history|ancient]], places the event at Jerusalem's northern gate, while another one, dated by Vincent and Abel to the [[Middle Ages]] and no earlier than the 12th century, locates it at the eastern gate.<ref name=\"Corpus\">{{cite book |series=Corpus Inscriptionum Iudeae/Palaestinae |title=Jerusalem, Part 2: 705\u20131120 |editors=Hannah M. Cotton, Leah Di Segni, Werner Eck, Benjamin Isaac, Alla Kushnir-Stein, Haggai Misgav, Jonathan J. Price, Ada Yardeni |year=2012 |volume=1 |publisher=De Gruyter |page=275 |isbn=978-3-11-025188-3 |quote=.... St. Stephen's Gate (Lions' gate; Bab Sitti Mariam). The gate owes its name to a tradition according to which Stephen the Deacon, the first martyr, was stoned on this spot. At the beginning of the 20 c. the Greek Orthodox Patriarchy built a church dedicated to the Protomartyr in their property in front of the gate, in an endeavour to pinpoint the tradition of the site, which was falling into oblivion following the construction of the Dominican church and monastery on the site of the Eudocian church of St. Stephen north of [[Damascus Gate]]. The Greek builders went so far as to maintain that, in digging the foundations of the new church, they had found a broken lintel with an engraved invocation to Saint Stephen, but their claim, accepted by Macalister and Vailh\u00e9, was promptly disproved by Vincent, who was able to show that the lintel came in fact from Beersheba. Vincent and Abel maintained that the tradition about Stephen's stoning at the eastern gate of Jerusalem was not earlier than the 12 c., while the tradition pointing to the northern gate was ancient. .... J. Milik .... suggested that all the tombstones discovered in this area belonged to the cemetery of the Probatica. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2cfmBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA275&lpg=PA275&dq=%22saint+stephen%22+%22stoning%22+%22Damascus+Gate%22+%22Lions+Gate%22&source=bl&ots=n2akgLH5jF&sig=M-FxMfuOkOWrY-_kJS7IFxo3ELg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibkbOOtuzOAhWYOsAKHUKlAxMQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=%22saint%20stephen%22%20%22stoning%22%20%22Damascus%20Gate%22%20%22Lions%20Gate%22&f=false |accessdate=31 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Views of Stephen's speech==\n[[File:Luis de Morales - St Stephen.jpg|thumb|upright|''Saint Stephen'' by [[Luis de Morales]]]]\nOf the numerous speeches in Acts of the Apostles, Stephen's speech to the Sanhedrin is the longest.<ref name=\"Koivisto\">{{cite web|url=http://faculty.gordon.edu/hu/bi/Ted_Hildebrandt/NTeSources/NTArticles/GTJ-NT/Koivisto-Acts7Stephen-GTJ-87.pdf| author=Rex A. Koivisto |title=Stephen's Speech: A Theology of Errors? |year= 1987|publisher=Grace Theological College |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> To the objection that it seems unlikely that such a long speech could be reproduced in the text of Acts exactly as it was delivered, some Biblical scholars have replied that Stephen's speech shows a distinctive personality behind it.<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\nThere are at least five places where Stephen's re-telling of the stories of Israelite history diverges from the scriptures where these stories originated; for instance, Stephen says that Jacob's tomb was in [[Shechem]],{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:16}} but Genesis 50:13{{Bibleref2c|Genesis|50:13}} says Jacob's final resting place was a cave in Machpelah at [[Hebron]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:1}}<ref name=\"Williams\" />  Some theologians argue that these may not be discrepancies, but rather a condensing of historical events for people who were already familiar with them, thus saving space.<ref>{{cite book |last=Balge |first=Richard |date=2016 |title=The People's Bible: Acts |location=Milwaukee |publisher=Northwestern Publishing House |page=77 |isbn=978-0-8100-1190-8}}</ref> Other scholars consider them as errors. Still others interpret them as deliberate choices making theological points.<ref name=\"Koivisto\" />  Another possibility is that the discrepancies come from an ancient Jewish tradition which was not included in the scriptures or may have been popular among people of Jerusalem who were not scribes.<ref>Marian Wolniewicz as the translator of the Book of Acts from: The Millennium Holy Bible; Warsaw, 1980</ref> Numerous parallels between the accounts of Stephen in Acts and the [[Jesus]] of the [[Gospel]]s \u2013 they both perform miracles, they are both tried by the Sanhedrin, they both pray for forgiveness for their killers, for instance \u2013 have led to suspicions that the author of Acts has emphasised \u2013 in order to show the recipient that people become holy when they follow the example of Christ \u2013 or invented some (or all) of these.<ref name=\"Williams2\" /> The criticism of traditional Jewish belief and practice in Stephen's speech is very strong \u2013 when he says God does not live in a dwelling \"made by human hands\", referring to the Temple, he is using an expression often employed by Biblical texts to describe idols.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> \n\nSome people have laid the charge of anti-Judaism against the speech, for instance the priest and scholar of comparative religion [[S. G. F. Brandon]], who states: \"The anti-Jewish polemic of this speech reflects the attitude of the author of Acts.\"<ref>{{Cite book\n | last = Brandon\n | first = S. G. F.\n | title = ''Jesus and the Zealots: A Study of the Political Factor in Primitive Christianity''\n | publisher = Charles Scribner's Sons\n | year = 1967\n | page= 158\n | isbn =978-0-684-31010-7 }}</ref> Such a view does not match up with the text of the speech as Stephen refers to his hearers as \"brothers and fathers\", and refers to Abraham as \"our father\" in verse 2.\n\n==Tomb and relics of Stephen==\n[[File:Place of the stoning of St. Stephen in Jerusalem.JPG|thumb|Reputed site of the stoning of Stephen, Greek Orthodox Church of St Stephen, [[Kidron Valley]], Jerusalem]]\nActs 8:2{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:2}} says \"Godly men buried Stephen and mourned deeply for him,\" but the location where he was buried is not specified.\n\nIn 415 AD, a priest named [[Fr. Lucian|Lucian]] purportedly had a dream that revealed the location of Stephen's remains at [[Beit Jimal]]. After that, the relics of the protomartyr were taken in procession to the [[Dormition Abbey|Church of Hagia Sion]] on 26 December 415, making it the date for the feast of Saint Stephen. In 439, the relics were translated to a new church north of the Damascus Gate built by the empress [[Aelia Eudocia]] in honor of Saint Stephen. This church was destroyed in the 12th century. A 20th-century French Catholic church, Saint-\u00c9tienne, was built in its place, while another, the Greek Orthodox Church of St Stephen, was built outside the eastern gate of the city,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.goisrael.com/Tourism_Eng/Tourist%20Information/Christian%20Themes/Details/Pages/Saint%20Stephen%20Church%20%20%20chr.aspx |title= St Stephen Church |publisher= Ministry of Tourism, Government of Israel |accessdate= 3 April 2013}}</ref> which a second tradition holds to be the site of his martyrdom, rather than the northern location outside Damascus Gate (for the two traditions see [[Saint Stephen#Location of the martyrdom|here]]).\n\nThe [[Crusades|Crusaders]] initially called the main northern gate of Jerusalem \"Saint Stephen's Gate\" (in Latin, ''Porta Sancti Stephani''), highlighting its proximity to the site of martyrdom of Saint Stephen, marked by the church and monastery built by Empress Eudocia.<ref name=Boasp53>{{cite book |page=53 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6m0qsAMf0z4C&pg=PA53 |title= Jerusalem in the time of the crusades: society, landscape, and art in the Holy City under Frankish rule |author= Adrian J. Boas |edition= Illustrated, reprint |publisher=Routledge |year=2001 |isbn= 978-0-415-23000-1}}</ref> A different tradition is documented from the end of the Crusader period, after the disappearance of the Byzantine church: as Christian pilgrims were prohibited from approaching the militarily exposed northern city wall, the name \"Saint Stephen's Gate\" was transferred to the still accessible eastern gate, which bears this name until this day.<ref name=\"MurphyOConnor\">{{cite book |title=The Holy Land: An Oxford Archaeological Guide from Earliest Times to 1700 |series=Oxford Archaeological Guides |author=Jerome Murphy-O'Connor |year=2008 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=21 |isbn=978-0-19-923666-4 |quote=The local guides simply moved to the Kidron valley certain holy places, notably the church of Saint Stephen, which in reality were north of the city, and business went on as before. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=m3Yy9FDcT8gC&pg=PT48&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Bab%20el-Ghor&f=false |accessdate=2 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe relics of the protomartyr were later translated to Rome by [[Pope Pelagius II]] during the construction of the [[basilica]] of [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]]. They were interred alongside the relics of [[Saint Lawrence]], whose tomb is enshrined within the church. According to the [[Golden Legend]], the relics of Lawrence moved miraculously to one side to make room for those of Stephen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catholicsaints.info/golden-legend-invention-of-saint-stephen-protomartyr/|title=Golden Legend \u2013 Invention of Saint Stephen, Protomartyr|date=2014-11-15|website=CatholicSaints.Info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Imperial Regalia]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] includes a relic known as [[St. Stephen's Purse]] which is an elaborate gold and jewel-encrusted box believed to contain soil soaked with the blood of St. Stephen. The reliquary is likely a 9th-century creation.\n\nIn his book ''[[The City of God]]'', [[Augustine of Hippo]] describes the many miracles that occurred when part of the relics of Saint Stephen were brought to Africa.<ref>Augustine, [http://www.logoslibrary.org/augustine/city/2208.html City of God, Book XXII, Chapter 2], accessed 17 March 2018</ref>\n\nPart of the right arm of Saint Stephen is enshrined at [[Trinity Lavra of St. Sergius]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.johnsanidopoulos.com/2010/08/translation-of-relics-of-stephen.html|title=Translation of the Relics of Saint Stephen the Protomartyr|last=Sanidopoulos|first=John|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>{{dubious|Weak source, a blog, be it by a cleric. Many local traditions are not recognised beyond the district or country borders. It's not science anyhow, but does the set of relics in Rome lack the right hand bones? I.e., what do the Catholics say?|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Saint Stephen's Day==\n{{Main|Saint Stephen's Day}}\n\n===Public holidays===\nIn [[Western Christianity]], 26 December is called \"[[Saint Stephen's Day]]\", the \"Feast of Stephen\" mentioned in the English [[Christmas carol]] \"[[Good King Wenceslas]]\". It is a [[public holiday]] in many nations that were historically Catholic, Anglican or Lutheran, including Austria, Croatia, the [[Public holidays in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]], Hungary, Ireland, Luxembourg, Slovakia, Poland, Italy, Germany, Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Finland, Catalonia and the Balearic Isles. In Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the United Kingdom, the day is celebrated as \"[[Boxing Day]]\".\n\n===Western Christianity===\nIn the current norms for the [[liturgy]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], the feast is celebrated at the [[mass (liturgy)|Eucharist]], but, for the [[Liturgy of the Hours]], is restricted to the Hours during the day, with [[Vespers|Evening Prayer]] being reserved to the celebration of the [[octave (liturgical)|Octave]] of [[Christmas]]. Historically, the \"Invention of the Relics of Saint Stephen\" (i.e., their reputed discovery) was commemorated on 3 August.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of Saints'', ed. David Hugh Farmer, corr. ed. (Oxford : Clarendon Press, 1979), p. 361. {{ISBN|0198691203}}</ref> The feasts of both 26 December and 3 August have been used in dating clauses in historical documents produced in England.<ref>''Handbook of dates for students of British history'', ed. [[C. R. Cheney]]. New, rev. ed. (Cambridge : Cambridge University Press, 2000), pp. 59, 85. {{ISBN|0521770955}}</ref>\n\n===Eastern Christianity===\n[[File:Saint Stephen 11cent.jpg|thumb|upright|Byzantine icon, 11th century]]\nIn the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]], those [[Eastern Catholic Churches]] which follow the [[Byzantine Rite]], and in Oriental Orthodox Churches (e.g., Coptic, Syrian, Malankara) Saint Stephen's feast day is celebrated on 27 December. This day is also called the \"Third Day of the Nativity\" because it is the third day of the Christmas season.\n\nSome Orthodox churches, particularly in the west, follow a modified Julian calendar that places date names identically with the standard Gregorian calendar of widespread civil usage. In those churches, then, the date the feast is observed is generally known as 27 December. However, other Orthodox churches, including the Oriental Orthodox, continue to use the original Julian calendar. Throughout the 21st century, 27 December Julian will continue to fall on 9 January in the Gregorian calendar, and that is the date on which they observe the feast.\n\n===Armenian Liturgy===\nIn the Armenian Apostolic and Armenian Catholic Churches, Saint Stephen's Day falls on 25 December \u2013 the day on which the feast of the Nativity of Jesus (Christmas) falls in all other churches. This is because the Armenian churches maintain the decree of Constantine, which stipulated that the Nativity and Theophany of Jesus were to be celebrated on 6 January. In dioceses of the Armenian Church which use the Julian Calendar, Saint Stephen's Day falls on 7 January and Nativity/Theophany on 19 January (for the remainder of the 21st century Julian).\n\nIn the eucharistic celebration on this feast day, it is traditional for all deacons serving at the altar to wear a liturgical crown (Armenian: \u056d\u0578\u0575\u0580 ''khooyr''), which is one of the vestments worn only by priests on all other days of the year, the crown being in this instance a symbol of martyrdom.\n\n==Commemorative places==\n[[File:St-Stepanous-02.jpg|thumb|The [[Saint Stepanos Monastery|Saint Stephen Armenian Monastery]] of the 9th century near Jolfa, Iran]]\n[[File:StStephen GiacomoCavedone.jpg|thumb|Saint Stephen holding a [[Gospel Book]] in a 1601 painting by [[Giacomo Cavedone]].]]\n:'''''See also''': [[St. Stephen's Cathedral (disambiguation)|St. Stephen's Cathedral]], [[St. Stephen's Church (disambiguation)|St. Stephen's Church]]\nMany churches and other places commemorate Stephen. Among the most notable are the two sites in Jerusalem held by different traditions to be the place of his martyrdom, the [[Salesian]] monastery of [[Beit Jimal]] in [[Palestine]]{{Disambiguation needed|date=April 2020}} held to be the place where his remains were miraculously found, and the church of [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]] in Rome, where the saint's remains are said to be buried.\n\nImportant churches and sites dedicated to Saint Stephen are:\n\n===Armenian churches===\n* [[Lmbatavank|Saint Stephen Church of Lmbat]] of the 7th century, near the town of [[Artik]], [[Armenia]].\n* [[Saint Stepanos Monastery|Saint Stephen Armenian Monastery]] of the 9th century, near the city of [[Jolfa, Iran (city)|Jolfa]], northwestern [[Iran]].\n* [[St. Stepanos Church|St. Stepanos Armenian Church]] of [[Izmir]], [[Turkey]], built in 1863 and destroyed in September 1922 during the [[Great Fire of Smyrna|Catastrophe of Smyrna]].\n\n===Australia===\n* [[Cathedral of St Stephen, Brisbane|St Stephen's Cathedral]], [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] \u2013 is the primary Catholic place of worship in the archdiocese of Brisbane.\n\n===Austria===\n* [[Stephansdom]], [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] \u2013 the Cathedral of St. Stephen, founded 1147 and seat of the [[Archbishop of Vienna]]. Symbol of the city of Vienna and of Austria, has the tallest spire in Austria and is the \"centerpiece of Vienna\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://travel.usnews.com/Vienna_Austria/Things_To_Do/St_Stephen_s_Cathedral_Stephansdom_29825/ |title=St. Stephen's Cathedral (Stephansdom) |work=[[US News and World Report]] |access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===France===\n* [[Saint \u00c9tienne]], France, and [[Saint Etienne (disambiguation)|numerous other places named Saint \u00c9tienne]] in the French-speaking world (Saint \u00c9tienne is the French form of Saint Stephen).\n\n===India===\n\n* [[St. Stephen's Church, Kombuthurai]], built by [[Francis Xavier]] in [[India]] in 1542.\n* St. Stephen's knanaya Catholic Forane Church, Uzhavoor, kottayam, built 1631.\n* [[St. Stephen's Orthodox Cathedral, Kudassanad, Pandalam, Kerala]] the first Orthodox Cathedral of Saint Stephen in India.\n* [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi]].\n* [[St. Stephen's Church, Delhi]] and St. Stephen's Hospital, Delhi.\n* [[St. Stephen\u2019s School, Chandigarh]] founded in 1986.\n* St. Stephen's Church, Thope, is one of the parishes of the first diocese of India, Kollam. It is 216 years old and the patron of this parish is St. Stephen, the first Martyr of the Church and it is situated beside Kollam Beach.\n\n===Ireland===\n* [[St Stephen's Green]], [[Dublin]]. The largest of Dublin's Georgian squares and itself named after a former leper hospital near the site.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.phoenixpark.ie/media/St.%20Stephen's%20Green%20Visitor's%20Guide.pdf |title=St. Stephen\u2019s Green |access-date=12 January 2020 |work=[[Phoenix Park]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022040741/http://www.phoenixpark.ie/media/St.%20Stephen's%20Green%20Visitor's%20Guide.pdf |archive-date=22 October 2015 |publisher=The [[Office of Public Works]]}}</ref>\n*[[Church of St. Stephen, Tyrrellspass]], located in [[Tyrrellspass]], [[County Westmeath]].\n\n===Italy===\n* Rome \u2013 [[Santo Stefano al Monte Celio|Santo Stefano Rotondo]], a church built under the commission of Constantine I on the ruins of the Caelian Hill of Rome. Built in the 5th Century, it is the first church in Rome to have a circular floor plan, instead of the traditional [[Greek Cross|Greek]] or [[Latin cross]] designs. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/italy/rome-santo-stefano-rotondo|title=Santo Stefano Rotondo \u2013 Rome, Italy|publisher=}}</ref> \n* [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]], where Saint Stephen is said to be interred together with Saint Lawrence in the crypt, under the high altar.\n* Vatican City \u2013 [[Santo Stefano degli Abissini]], Coptic Christian church in Vatican City, that is also the [[National churches in Rome|National Church of Ethiopia in Rome]].\n* Milan \u2013 [[Basilica di Santo Stefano Maggiore]], a baroque church built in the fifth century and originally dedicated to both Saint Stephen and [[Zechariah (New Testament figure)|Saint Zecheriah]].\n\n===Palestine===\n* [[St. Stephen's Basilica, Jerusalem]], in French '''Saint-\u00c9tienne''', at the traditional place of St Stephen's martyrdom; modern church over ruins of Byzantine 5th-century predecessor.\n* '''St. Stephan's Gate''', the Christian name of one of the city gates of the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City]] of [[Jerusalem]], also known as the \"[[The Lions' Gate|Lions' Gate]]\". A post-Byzantine tradition holds that Stephen's stoning occurred there, while an older tradition connects the martyrdom to the Damascus Gate, where a [[St. Stephen's Basilica, Jerusalem|church]] and large monastic complex dedicated to Saint Stephen was built in the 5th century (see [[Saint Stephen#Location of the martyrdom|above]]). A modern Greek Orthodox Church of Saint Stephen stands a short distance from Lions' Gate.\n\n===United Kingdom===\n* [[St Stephen's Chapel]] in the [[Palace of Westminster]], London, was originally built in the reign of [[Henry III of England]]; it became the first site of the debating chamber of the [[British House of Commons]]. The tower that houses [[Big Ben]], that was properly called The Clock Tower, was referred to as St Stephen's Tower by Victorian journalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/enquiries/#jump-link-3|title=Frequently asked questions: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower|work=UK Parliament}}</ref> The Clock Tower was renamed Elizabeth Tower to commemorate the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] in 2013. St Stephen's Tower is the smaller tower in the middle of the building.\n* [[St Stephen's House, Oxford]] \u2013 a [[Permanent Private Hall]] of the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Anglican]] Theological College.\n* [[St Stephen's Church, Bristol]] \u2013 the first{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} city church built outside the walls c. 1250, rebuilt c. 1430\u20131490.\n\n==Other associations==\n* In the Catholic Church, the [[Guild of St. Stephen]] is an international association of [[altar server]]s whose aim is to promote \"highest standards of serving at the Church's liturgy\".<ref>[http://guildofststephen.org/ Guild of St. Stephen], accessed 21 March 2018</ref>\n* Saint Stephen is one of the sculptures on the side of the [[Orsanmichele]] in [[Florence, Italy|Florence]]. Saint Stephen is the patron saint of the [[Guilds of Florence|wool guild]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Portal:Catholic Church/Patron Archive/December 26|Saint Stephen, patron saint archive]]\n* [[Guilds of Florence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Saint Stephen}}\n{{Wikiquote|Stephanus}}\n* [http://www.bartleby.com/210/12/261.html \"Saint Stephen, the First Martyr\"]\n* [http://orthodoxwiki.org/Apostle_Stephen_the_Protomartyr \"Apostle Stephen the Protomartyr\"]\n* [http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/st.-stephens-death-shows-importance-of-scripture-pope-says/ Benedict XVI, \"Reflection on the Life and Death of Saint Stephen\"]\n* [http://www.stpetersbasilica.info/Exterior/Colonnades/Saints/St%20Stephen-98/StStephen.htm Colonnade Statue in St Peter's Square]\n* {{Hl-Lex|b|Stephanus.htm}}\n\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{History of the Catholic Church}}\n{{New Testament people}}\n{{History of Christianity}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephen, Saint}}\n[[Category:1st-century births]]\n[[Category:34 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:Early Jewish Christians]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Jews]]\n[[Category:People executed for heresy]]\n[[Category:People executed by stoning]]\n[[Category:People in Acts of the Apostles]]\n[[Category:Wonderworkers]]\n[[Category:Visions of Jesus and Mary]]\n[[Category:Burials at San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]]\n[[Category:Christian martyrs]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|Deacon Stephen, a martyred saint|the first king of Hungary|Stephen I of Hungary|other uses|St. Stephen (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|1st-century early Christian martyr and saint}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox saint\n|name         = Saint Stephen\n|image        = Polittico del 1476, s. stefano.jpg\n|imagesize    = 200px\n|caption      = ''Saint Stephan'' by [[Carlo Crivelli]]\n|titles       = [[Deacon]] <br>Protomartyr of The Faith\n|birth_date   = AD 5\n|death_date= AD 33-37 (aged 28-32)\n|death_place  = [[Jerusalem]], [[Judaea]], [[Roman Empire]]\n|feast_day    = 25 December ([[Armenian Christianity]])<br>26 December (Western)<br>27 December (Eastern)<br>Tobi 1 ([[Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria|Coptic Christianity]])\n|canonized_date= [[Pre-Congregation]]\n|canonized_place=\n|canonized_by=\n|major_shrine=\n|attributes   = [[Christian martyrs#Degrees of martyrdom|Red Martyr]], stones, [[dalmatic]], [[censer]], miniature church, [[Gospel Book]], [[martyr's palm]]. In [[Eastern Christianity]] he often wears an [[orarion]]\n|patronage    = [[Altar server|Altar Servers]] [http://totus2us.com/vocation/saints/st-stephen/];[[Acoma Pueblo|Acoma]] Indian [[Pueblo]]; [[casket]] makers; [[Cetona|Cetona, Italy]]; [[deacons]]; [[headache]]s; [[horse]]s; [[Kessel, Belgium]]; [[masonry|masons]]; [[Owensboro, Kentucky]]; [[Passau|Passau, Germany]]; [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]]; [[Dodoma]], [[Tanzania]]; [[Serbia]]; [[Republic of Srpska]]; [[Prato|Prato, Italy]] [http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-stephen-the-martyr/]\n|issues=\n|suppressed_date=\n|venerated_in = [[Roman Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Catholic Church]]es<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]]<br/>[[Oriental Orthodox Church]]es<br/>[[Assyrian Church of the East]]<br/>[[Anglican Communion]]\n}}\n\n'''Stephen''' ({{lang-grc-gre|\u03a3\u03c4\u03ad\u03c6\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2}} ''St\u00e9phanos'', meaning \"wreath, crown\" and by extension \"reward, honor\", often given as a title rather than as a name, {{lang-he|\u05e1\u05d8\u05e4\u05e0\u05d5\u05e1 \u05d4\u05e7\u05d3\u05d5\u05e9}}), (c. AD 5 \u2013 c. AD 34) traditionally venerated as the [[protomartyr]] or first martyr of [[Christianity]],<ref name=ssdca>[http://www.ssdca.org/ssdca/index.cfm/st-stephen-bio/ \"St. Stephen the Deacon\"], St. Stephen Diaconal Community Association, Roman Catholic Diocese of Rochester.</ref> was according to the [[Acts of the Apostles]] a [[deacon]] in the early church at [[Jerusalem]] who aroused the enmity of members of various [[synagogue]]s by his teachings. Accused of [[blasphemy]] at his trial, he made a speech denouncing the Jewish authorities who were sitting in judgment on him and was then [[stoned to death]]. His [[martyrdom]] was witnessed by [[Saul of Tarsus]], a [[Pharisee]] who would later become a follower of Jesus and known as [[Paul the Apostle]].\n\nThe only primary source for information about Stephen is the [[New Testament]] book of the Acts of the Apostles.<ref name=\"Newadvent\">{{cite web |url=http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/14286b.htm |title=Saint Stephen \n|author=Souvay, Charles|date= |work=Catholic Encyclopedia,1912 |publisher=New Advent |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref>  Stephen is mentioned in [[Acts 6]] as one of the Greek-speaking [[Hellenistic Jew]]s selected to participate in a fairer distribution of welfare to the Greek-speaking widows.<ref>Mal Couch, ''A Bible Handbook to the Acts of the Apostles'', 2003, p. 246. \"Stephen is distinguished as \"a man full of faith and of the Holy Spirit\" (Acts 6:5). Stephen and the other men were Hellenistic Jews whose native language was Greek. He had lived with Gentiles in other parts of the Roman Empire.\"</ref>\n\nThe [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], [[Anglican]], [[Oriental Orthodox]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]es, and the [[Church of the East]] venerate Stephen as a [[saint]]. The [[Lutheran]] Church recognizes Stephen as a saint as it recognizes all Christians as saints.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1580boc.org/ap/xxi-ix |title=Article XXI (IX) Of the Invocation of the Saints}}</ref> Traditionally, Stephen is invested with a crown of martyrdom; artistic representations often depict him with three stones and the [[Palm branch (symbol)|martyr's palm frond]]. Eastern Christian [[iconography]] shows him as a young, beardless man with a [[tonsure]], wearing a deacon's [[vestments]], and often holding a miniature church building or a [[censer]].\n\n==Martyrdom==\n===Background===\n\nStephen is first mentioned in the [[Acts of the Apostles]] as one of [[seven deacons]] appointed by the [[Apostle]]s to distribute food and charitable aid to poorer members of the community in the early church. According to Orthodox belief, he was the eldest and is therefore called \"archdeacon\".<ref name=oca>{{cite web|url=http://oca.org/saints/lives/2015/12/27/103659-protomartyr-and-archdeacon-stephen|title=Protomartyr and Archdeacon Stephen|publisher=}}</ref> As another deacon, Nicholas of Antioch, is specifically stated to have been a convert to [[Judaism]], it may be assumed that Stephen was born Jewish, but nothing more is known about his previous life.<ref name=\"Newadvent\"/> The reason for the appointment of the deacons is stated to have been dissatisfaction among [[Hellenistic]] (that is, Greek-influenced and Greek-speaking) Jews that their widows were being slighted in preference to Hebraic ones in the d . \n And then he saw thanos he thought it was a grape so he ate it. then he was in endgame for a little ans snapped hus  is Greek, it has been assumed that he was one of these Hellenistic Jews. Stephen is stated to have been full of faith and the Holy Spirit and\n to have performed miracles among the people.{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:5, 8}} \n[[File:St stephen.jpg|thumb|upright|''Stoning of Saint Stephen'', altarpiece of San Giorgio Maggiore, Venice, by Jacopo & Domenico [[Tintoretto]]]]\nIt seems to have been among synagogues of Hellenistic Jews that he performed his teachings and \"signs and wonders\" since it is said that he aroused the opposition of the \"[[Synagogue of the Libertines|Synagogue of the Freedmen]]\", and \"of the Cyrenians, and of the Alexandrians, and of them that were of Cilicia and Asia\".{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:9}} Members of these synagogues had challenged Stephen's teachings, but Stephen had bested them in debate. Furious at this humiliation, they suborned false testimony that Stephen had preached blasphemy against [[Moses]] and God. They dragged him to appear before the [[Sanhedrin]], the supreme legal court of Jewish elders, accusing him of preaching against the [[Second Temple|Temple]] and the [[Torah|Mosaic Law]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|6:9\u201314}} Stephen is said to have been unperturbed, his face looking like \"that of an angel\".<ref name=\"Newadvent\"/>\n\n===Speech to Sanhedrin===\nIn a long speech to the [[Sanhedrin]] comprising almost the whole of [[Acts 7|Acts chapter 7]], Stephen presents his view of the history of [[Israel]]. The God of glory, he says, appeared to [[Abraham]] in [[Mesopotamia]], thus establishing at the beginning of the speech one of its major themes, that God does not dwell only in one particular building (meaning the Temple).<ref name=\"Williams\">David J. Williams (1989), ''Acts (Understanding the Bible Commentary Series)'', Baker Books, Chapter 16, {{ISBN|978-0-8010-4805-0}}.</ref> Stephen recounts the stories of the [[patriarchs]] in some depth, and goes into even more detail in the case of [[Moses]]. God appeared to Moses in the burning bush,{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:30\u201332}} and inspired Moses to lead his people out of Egypt. Nevertheless, the Israelites turned to other gods.{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:39\u201343}} This establishes the second main theme of Stephen's speech, Israel's disobedience to God.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> Stephen faced two accusations: that he had declared that Jesus would destroy the Temple in Jerusalem and that he had changed the customs of Moses. [[Benedict XVI]] stated that St. Stephen appealed to the Jewish scriptures to prove how the laws of Moses were not subverted by Jesus but, instead, were being fulfilled.<ref>Kerr, David. [http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/st.-stephens-death-shows-importance-of-scripture-pope-says/ \"St. Stephen\u2019s death shows importance of Scripture, Pope says\"], Catholic News Agency, 2 May 2012.</ref> Stephen denounces his listeners<ref name=\"Williams\" /> as \"stiff-necked\" people who, just as their ancestors had done, resist the Holy Spirit. \"Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute? They even killed those who predicted the coming of the Righteous One. And now you have betrayed and murdered him.\"{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:51\u201353}}\n\n===The stoning of Stephen===\n[[File:Giovanni Battista Lucini - Martyrdom of St. Stephen.JPG|thumb|260px|''Stoning of Saint Stephen'' by [[Giovanni Battista Lucini]]]]\n\nThus castigated, the account is that the crowd could contain their anger no longer.<ref>[http://www.ewtn.com/library/MARY/STEPHEN2.HTM\"Lives of Saints\", John J. Crawley & Co., Inc.]</ref> However, Stephen looked up and cried, \"Look! I see heaven open and the [[Son of Man]] standing on the right hand of God!\" He said that the recently executed Jesus was standing by the side of God.<ref name=\"Williams2\">David J. Williams, ''Acts (Understanding the Bible Commentary Series)'', Baker Books 1989, chapter 17, {{ISBN|978-0-8010-4805-0}}</ref>{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:54}} The people from the crowd, who threw the first stones<ref>{{Bibleverse||Deuteronomy|13:9|HE}} and {{Bibleverse||Deuteronomy|17:7|HE}}</ref><ref name=\"Williams2\" /> laid their coats down so as to be able to do this, at the feet of a \"young man named Saul\" (later known as [[Paul the Apostle]]). Stephen prayed that the Lord would receive his spirit and his killers be forgiven, sank to his knees, and \"fell asleep\".{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:58\u201360}} Saul \"approved of their killing him.\"{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:1}} In the aftermath of Stephen's death, the remaining disciples fled to distant lands, many to [[Antioch]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|11:19\u201320}}<ref>{{Cite book |last=Unger |first=Merrill F. |authorlink=Merrill Unger |editor-last=Harrison |editor-first=R. K. |year=2006 |origyear=1957 |title=The New Unger's Bible Dictionary |url= |location=Chicago |publisher=Moody Publishers |at=\"Antioch\" |isbn=978-0-8024-9066-7 }}</ref>\n\n====Location of the martyrdom====\nThe exact site of Stephen's stoning is not mentioned in Acts; instead there are two different traditions. One, claimed by noted French archaeologists [[Louis-Hugues Vincent]] (1872\u20131960) and [[F\u00e9lix-Marie Abel]] (1878\u20131953) to be [[Ancient history|ancient]], places the event at Jerusalem's northern gate, while another one, dated by Vincent and Abel to the [[Middle Ages]] and no earlier than the 12th century, locates it at the eastern gate.<ref name=\"Corpus\">{{cite book |series=Corpus Inscriptionum Iudeae/Palaestinae |title=Jerusalem, Part 2: 705\u20131120 |editors=Hannah M. Cotton, Leah Di Segni, Werner Eck, Benjamin Isaac, Alla Kushnir-Stein, Haggai Misgav, Jonathan J. Price, Ada Yardeni |year=2012 |volume=1 |publisher=De Gruyter |page=275 |isbn=978-3-11-025188-3 |quote=.... St. Stephen's Gate (Lions' gate; Bab Sitti Mariam). The gate owes its name to a tradition according to which Stephen the Deacon, the first martyr, was stoned on this spot. At the beginning of the 20 c. the Greek Orthodox Patriarchy built a church dedicated to the Protomartyr in their property in front of the gate, in an endeavour to pinpoint the tradition of the site, which was falling into oblivion following the construction of the Dominican church and monastery on the site of the Eudocian church of St. Stephen north of [[Damascus Gate]]. The Greek builders went so far as to maintain that, in digging the foundations of the new church, they had found a broken lintel with an engraved invocation to Saint Stephen, but their claim, accepted by Macalister and Vailh\u00e9, was promptly disproved by Vincent, who was able to show that the lintel came in fact from Beersheba. Vincent and Abel maintained that the tradition about Stephen's stoning at the eastern gate of Jerusalem was not earlier than the 12 c., while the tradition pointing to the northern gate was ancient. .... J. Milik .... suggested that all the tombstones discovered in this area belonged to the cemetery of the Probatica. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=2cfmBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA275&lpg=PA275&dq=%22saint+stephen%22+%22stoning%22+%22Damascus+Gate%22+%22Lions+Gate%22&source=bl&ots=n2akgLH5jF&sig=M-FxMfuOkOWrY-_kJS7IFxo3ELg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwibkbOOtuzOAhWYOsAKHUKlAxMQ6AEIJjAC#v=onepage&q=%22saint%20stephen%22%20%22stoning%22%20%22Damascus%20Gate%22%20%22Lions%20Gate%22&f=false |accessdate=31 August 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Views of Stephen's speech==\n[[File:Luis de Morales - St Stephen.jpg|thumb|upright|''Saint Stephen'' by [[Luis de Morales]]]]\nOf the numerous speeches in Acts of the Apostles, Stephen's speech to the Sanhedrin is the longest.<ref name=\"Koivisto\">{{cite web|url=http://faculty.gordon.edu/hu/bi/Ted_Hildebrandt/NTeSources/NTArticles/GTJ-NT/Koivisto-Acts7Stephen-GTJ-87.pdf| author=Rex A. Koivisto |title=Stephen's Speech: A Theology of Errors? |year= 1987|publisher=Grace Theological College |accessdate=3 April 2013}}</ref> To the objection that it seems unlikely that such a long speech could be reproduced in the text of Acts exactly as it was delivered, some Biblical scholars have replied that Stephen's speech shows a distinctive personality behind it.<ref name=\"Williams\" />\n\nThere are at least five places where Stephen's re-telling of the stories of Israelite history diverges from the scriptures where these stories originated; for instance, Stephen says that Jacob's tomb was in [[Shechem]],{{Bibleref2c|Acts|7:16}} but Genesis 50:13{{Bibleref2c|Genesis|50:13}} says Jacob's final resting place was a cave in Machpelah at [[Hebron]].{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:1}}<ref name=\"Williams\" />  Some theologians argue that these may not be discrepancies, but rather a condensing of historical events for people who were already familiar with them, thus saving space.<ref>{{cite book |last=Balge |first=Richard |date=2016 |title=The People's Bible: Acts |location=Milwaukee |publisher=Northwestern Publishing House |page=77 |isbn=978-0-8100-1190-8}}</ref> Other scholars consider them as errors. Still others interpret them as deliberate choices making theological points.<ref name=\"Koivisto\" />  Another possibility is that the discrepancies come from an ancient Jewish tradition which was not included in the scriptures or may have been popular among people of Jerusalem who were not scribes.<ref>Marian Wolniewicz as the translator of the Book of Acts from: The Millennium Holy Bible; Warsaw, 1980</ref> Numerous parallels between the accounts of Stephen in Acts and the [[Jesus]] of the [[Gospel]]s \u2013 they both perform miracles, they are both tried by the Sanhedrin, they both pray for forgiveness for their killers, for instance \u2013 have led to suspicions that the author of Acts has emphasised \u2013 in order to show the recipient that people become holy when they follow the example of Christ \u2013 or invented some (or all) of these.<ref name=\"Williams2\" /> The criticism of traditional Jewish belief and practice in Stephen's speech is very strong \u2013 when he says God does not live in a dwelling \"made by human hands\", referring to the Temple, he is using an expression often employed by Biblical texts to describe idols.<ref name=\"Williams\" /> \n\nSome people have laid the charge of anti-Judaism against the speech, for instance the priest and scholar of comparative religion [[S. G. F. Brandon]], who states: \"The anti-Jewish polemic of this speech reflects the attitude of the author of Acts.\"<ref>{{Cite book\n | last = Brandon\n | first = S. G. F.\n | title = ''Jesus and the Zealots: A Study of the Political Factor in Primitive Christianity''\n | publisher = Charles Scribner's Sons\n | year = 1967\n | page= 158\n | isbn =978-0-684-31010-7 }}</ref> Such a view does not match up with the text of the speech as Stephen refers to his hearers as \"brothers and fathers\", and refers to Abraham as \"our father\" in verse 2.\n\n==Tomb and relics of Stephen==\n[[File:Place of the stoning of St. Stephen in Jerusalem.JPG|thumb|Reputed site of the stoning of Stephen, Greek Orthodox Church of St Stephen, [[Kidron Valley]], Jerusalem]]\nActs 8:2{{Bibleref2c|Acts|8:2}} says \"Godly men buried Stephen and mourned deeply for him,\" but the location where he was buried is not specified.\n\nIn 415 AD, a priest named [[Fr. Lucian|Lucian]] purportedly had a dream that revealed the location of Stephen's remains at [[Beit Jimal]]. After that, the relics of the protomartyr were taken in procession to the [[Dormition Abbey|Church of Hagia Sion]] on 26 December 415, making it the date for the feast of Saint Stephen. In 439, the relics were translated to a new church north of the Damascus Gate built by the empress [[Aelia Eudocia]] in honor of Saint Stephen. This church was destroyed in the 12th century. A 20th-century French Catholic church, Saint-\u00c9tienne, was built in its place, while another, the Greek Orthodox Church of St Stephen, was built outside the eastern gate of the city,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.goisrael.com/Tourism_Eng/Tourist%20Information/Christian%20Themes/Details/Pages/Saint%20Stephen%20Church%20%20%20chr.aspx |title= St Stephen Church |publisher= Ministry of Tourism, Government of Israel |accessdate= 3 April 2013}}</ref> which a second tradition holds to be the site of his martyrdom, rather than the northern location outside Damascus Gate (for the two traditions see [[Saint Stephen#Location of the martyrdom|here]]).\n\nThe [[Crusades|Crusaders]] initially called the main northern gate of Jerusalem \"Saint Stephen's Gate\" (in Latin, ''Porta Sancti Stephani''), highlighting its proximity to the site of martyrdom of Saint Stephen, marked by the church and monastery built by Empress Eudocia.<ref name=Boasp53>{{cite book |page=53 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=6m0qsAMf0z4C&pg=PA53 |title= Jerusalem in the time of the crusades: society, landscape, and art in the Holy City under Frankish rule |author= Adrian J. Boas |edition= Illustrated, reprint |publisher=Routledge |year=2001 |isbn= 978-0-415-23000-1}}</ref> A different tradition is documented from the end of the Crusader period, after the disappearance of the Byzantine church: as Christian pilgrims were prohibited from approaching the militarily exposed northern city wall, the name \"Saint Stephen's Gate\" was transferred to the still accessible eastern gate, which bears this name until this day.<ref name=\"MurphyOConnor\">{{cite book |title=The Holy Land: An Oxford Archaeological Guide from Earliest Times to 1700 |series=Oxford Archaeological Guides |author=Jerome Murphy-O'Connor |year=2008 |location=Oxford |publisher=Oxford University Press |page=21 |isbn=978-0-19-923666-4 |quote=The local guides simply moved to the Kidron valley certain holy places, notably the church of Saint Stephen, which in reality were north of the city, and business went on as before. |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=m3Yy9FDcT8gC&pg=PT48&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Bab%20el-Ghor&f=false |accessdate=2 March 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe relics of the protomartyr were later translated to Rome by [[Pope Pelagius II]] during the construction of the [[basilica]] of [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]]. They were interred alongside the relics of [[Saint Lawrence]], whose tomb is enshrined within the church. According to the [[Golden Legend]], the relics of Lawrence moved miraculously to one side to make room for those of Stephen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://catholicsaints.info/golden-legend-invention-of-saint-stephen-protomartyr/|title=Golden Legend \u2013 Invention of Saint Stephen, Protomartyr|date=2014-11-15|website=CatholicSaints.Info|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Imperial Regalia]] of the [[Holy Roman Empire]] includes a relic known as [[St. Stephen's Purse]] which is an elaborate gold and jewel-encrusted box believed to contain soil soaked with the blood of St. Stephen. The reliquary is likely a 9th century creation.\n\nIn his book ''[[The City of God]]'', [[Augustine of Hippo]] describes the many miracles that occurred when part of the relics of Saint Stephen were brought to Africa.<ref>Augustine, [http://www.logoslibrary.org/augustine/city/2208.html City of God, Book XXII, Chapter 2], accessed 17 March 2018</ref>\n\nPart of the right arm of Saint Stephen is enshrined at [[Trinity Lavra of St. Sergius]] in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.johnsanidopoulos.com/2010/08/translation-of-relics-of-stephen.html|title=Translation of the Relics of Saint Stephen the Protomartyr|last=Sanidopoulos|first=John|access-date=2020-02-19}}</ref>{{dubious|Weak source, a blog, be it by a cleric. Many local traditions are not recognised beyond the district or country borders. It's not science anyhow, but does the set of relics in Rome lack the right hand bones? I.e., what do the Catholics say?|date=August 2016}}\n\n==Saint Stephen's Day==\n{{Main|Saint Stephen's Day}}\n\n===Public holidays===\nIn [[Western Christianity]], 26 December is called \"[[Saint Stephen's Day]]\", the \"Feast of Stephen\" mentioned in the English [[Christmas carol]] \"[[Good King Wenceslas]]\". It is a [[public holiday]] in many nations that were historically Catholic, Anglican or Lutheran, including Austria, Croatia, the [[Public holidays in the Czech Republic|Czech Republic]], Hungary, Ireland, Luxembourg, Slovakia, Poland, Italy, Germany, Norway, Sweden, Denmark, Finland, Catalonia and the Balearic Isles. In Australia, New Zealand, Canada and the United Kingdom, the day is celebrated as \"[[Boxing Day]]\".\n\n===Western Christianity===\nIn the current norms for the [[liturgy]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]], the feast is celebrated at the [[mass (liturgy)|Eucharist]], but, for the [[Liturgy of the Hours]], is restricted to the Hours during the day, with [[Vespers|Evening Prayer]] being reserved to the celebration of the [[octave (liturgical)|Octave]] of [[Christmas]]. Historically, the \"Invention of the Relics of Saint Stephen\" (i.e., their reputed discovery) was commemorated on 3 August.<ref>''Oxford Dictionary of Saints'', ed. David Hugh Farmer, corr. ed. (Oxford : Clarendon Press, 1979), p. 361. {{ISBN|0198691203}}</ref> The feasts of both 26 December and 3 August have been used in dating clauses in historical documents produced in England.<ref>''Handbook of dates for students of British history'', ed. [[C. R. Cheney]]. New, rev. ed. (Cambridge : Cambridge University Press, 2000), pp. 59, 85. {{ISBN|0521770955}}</ref>\n\n===Eastern Christianity===\n[[File:Saint Stephen 11cent.jpg|thumb|upright|Byzantine icon, 11th century]]\nIn the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]], those [[Eastern Catholic Churches]] which follow the [[Byzantine Rite]], and in Oriental Orthodox Churches (e.g., Coptic, Syrian, Malankara) Saint Stephen's feast day is celebrated on 27 December. This day is also called the \"Third Day of the Nativity\" because it is the third day of the Christmas season.\n\nSome Orthodox churches, particularly in the west, follow a modified Julian calendar that places date names identically with the standard Gregorian calendar of widespread civil usage. In those churches, then, the date the feast is observed is generally known as 27 December. However, other Orthodox churches, including the Oriental Orthodox, continue to use the original Julian calendar. Throughout the 21st century, 27 December Julian will continue to fall on 9 January in the Gregorian calendar, and that is the date on which they observe the feast.\n\n===Armenian Liturgy===\nIn the Armenian Apostolic and Armenian Catholic Churches, Saint Stephen's Day falls on 25 December \u2013 the day on which the feast of the Nativity of Jesus (Christmas) falls in all other churches. This is because the Armenian churches maintain the decree of Constantine, which stipulated that the Nativity and Theophany of Jesus were to be celebrated on 6 January. In dioceses of the Armenian Church which use the Julian Calendar, Saint Stephen's Day falls on 7 January and Nativity/Theophany on 19 January (for the remainder of the 21st century Julian).\n\nIn the eucharistic celebration on this feast day, it is traditional for all deacons serving at the altar to wear a liturgical crown (Armenian: \u056d\u0578\u0575\u0580 ''khooyr''), which is one of the vestments worn only by priests on all other days of the year, the crown being in this instance a symbol of martyrdom.\n\n==Commemorative places==\n[[File:St-Stepanous-02.jpg|thumb|The [[Saint Stepanos Monastery|Saint Stephen Armenian Monastery]] of the 9th century near Jolfa, Iran]]\n[[File:StStephen GiacomoCavedone.jpg|thumb|Saint Stephen holding a [[Gospel Book]] in a 1601 painting by [[Giacomo Cavedone]].]]\n:'''''See also''': [[St. Stephen's Cathedral (disambiguation)|St. Stephen's Cathedral]], [[St. Stephen's Church (disambiguation)|St. Stephen's Church]]\nMany churches and other places commemorate Stephen. Among the most notable are the two sites in Jerusalem held by different traditions to be the place of his martyrdom, the [[Salesian]] monastery of [[Beit Jimal]] in [[Palestine]] held to be the place where his remains were miraculously found, and the church of [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]] in Rome, where the saint's remains are said to be buried.\n\nImportant churches and sites dedicated to Saint Stephen are:\n\n===Armenian churches===\n* [[Lmbatavank|Saint Stephen Church of Lmbat]] of the 7th century, near the town of [[Artik]], [[Armenia]].\n* [[Saint Stepanos Monastery|Saint Stephen Armenian Monastery]] of the 9th century, near the city of [[Jolfa, Iran (city)|Jolfa]], northwestern [[Iran]].\n* [[St. Stepanos Church|St. Stepanos Armenian Church]] of [[Izmir]], [[Turkey]], built in 1863 and destroyed in September 1922 during the [[Great Fire of Smyrna|Catastrophe of Smyrna]].\n\n===Australia===\n* [[Cathedral of St Stephen, Brisbane|St Stephen's Cathedral]], [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] \u2013 is the primary Catholic place of worship in the archdiocese of Brisbane.\n\n===Austria===\n* [[Stephansdom]], [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] \u2013 the Cathedral of St. Stephen, founded 1147 and seat of the [[Archbishop of Vienna]]. Symbol of the city of Vienna and of Austria, has the tallest spire in Austria and is the \"centerpiece of Vienna\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://travel.usnews.com/Vienna_Austria/Things_To_Do/St_Stephen_s_Cathedral_Stephansdom_29825/ |title=St. Stephen's Cathedral (Stephansdom) |work=[[US News and World Report]] |access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===France===\n* [[Saint \u00c9tienne]], France, and [[Saint Etienne (disambiguation)|numerous other places named Saint \u00c9tienne]] in the French-speaking world (Saint \u00c9tienne is the French form of Saint Stephen).\n\n===India===\n\n* [[St. Stephen's Church, Kombuthurai]], built by [[Francis Xavier]] in [[India]] in 1542.\n* St. Stephen's knanaya Catholic Forane Church, Uzhavoor, kottayam, built 1631.\n* [[St. Stephen's Orthodox Cathedral, Kudassanad, Pandalam, Kerala]] the first Orthodox Cathedral of Saint Stephen in India.\n* [[St. Stephen's College, Delhi]].\n* [[St. Stephen's Church, Delhi]] and St. Stephen's Hospital, Delhi.\n* [[St. Stephen\u2019s School, Chandigarh]] founded in 1986.\n* St. Stephen's Church, Thope, is one of the parishes of the first diocese of India, Kollam. It is 216 years old and the patron of this parish is St. Stephen, the first Martyr of the Church and it is situated beside Kollam Beach.\n\n===Ireland===\n* [[St Stephen's Green]], [[Dublin]]. The largest of Dublin's Georgian squares and itself named after a former leper hospital near the site.<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.phoenixpark.ie/media/St.%20Stephen's%20Green%20Visitor's%20Guide.pdf |title=St. Stephen\u2019s Green |access-date=12 January 2020 |work=[[Phoenix Park]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151022040741/http://www.phoenixpark.ie/media/St.%20Stephen's%20Green%20Visitor's%20Guide.pdf |archive-date=22 October 2015 |publisher=The [[Office of Public Works]]}}</ref>\n*[[Church of St. Stephen, Tyrrellspass]], located in [[Tyrrellspass]], [[County Westmeath]].\n\n===Italy===\n* Rome \u2013 [[Santo Stefano al Monte Celio|Santo Stefano Rotondo]], a church built under the commission of Constantine I on the ruins of the Caelian Hill of Rome. Built in the 5th Century, it is the first church in Rome to have a circular floor plan, instead of the traditional [[Greek Cross|Greek]] or [[Latin cross]] designs. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-destinations.com/italy/rome-santo-stefano-rotondo|title=Santo Stefano Rotondo \u2013 Rome, Italy|publisher=}}</ref> \n* [[San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]], where Saint Stephen is said to be interred together with Saint Lawrence in the crypt, under the high altar.\n* Vatican City \u2013 [[Santo Stefano degli Abissini]], Coptic Christian church in Vatican City, that is also the [[National churches in Rome|National Church of Ethiopia in Rome]].\n* Milan \u2013 [[Basilica di Santo Stefano Maggiore]], a baroque church built in the fifth century and originally dedicated to both Saint Stephen and [[Zechariah (New Testament figure)|Saint Zecheriah]].\n\n===Palestine===\n* [[St. Stephen's Basilica, Jerusalem]], in French '''Saint-\u00c9tienne''', at the traditional place of St Stephen's martyrdom; modern church over ruins of Byzantine 5th-century predecessor.\n* '''St. Stephan's Gate''', the Christian name of one of the city gates of the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City]] of [[Jerusalem]], also known as the \"[[The Lions' Gate|Lions' Gate]]\". A post-Byzantine tradition holds that Stephen's stoning occurred there, while an older tradition connects the martyrdom to the Damascus Gate, where a [[St. Stephen's Basilica, Jerusalem|church]] and large monastic complex dedicated to Saint Stephen was built in the 5th century (see [[Saint Stephen#Location of the martyrdom|above]]). A modern Greek Orthodox Church of Saint Stephen stands a short distance from Lions' Gate.\n\n===United Kingdom===\n* [[St Stephen's Chapel]] in the [[Palace of Westminster]], London, was originally built in the reign of [[Henry III of England]]; it became the first site of the debating chamber of the [[British House of Commons]]. The tower that houses [[Big Ben]], that was properly called The Clock Tower, was referred to as St Stephen's Tower by Victorian journalists.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/building/palace/big-ben/enquiries/#jump-link-3|title=Frequently asked questions: Big Ben and Elizabeth Tower|work=UK Parliament}}</ref> The Clock Tower was renamed Elizabeth Tower to commemorate the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] in 2013. St Stephen's Tower is the smaller tower in the middle of the building.\n* [[St Stephen's House, Oxford]] \u2013 a [[Permanent Private Hall]] of the [[University of Oxford]] and [[Anglican]] Theological College.\n* [[St Stephen's Church, Bristol]] \u2013 the first{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} city church built outside the walls c. 1250, rebuilt c. 1430\u20131490.\n\n==Other associations==\n* In the Catholic Church, the [[Guild of St. Stephen]] is an international association of [[altar server]]s whose aim is to promote \"highest standards of serving at the Church's liturgy\".<ref>[http://guildofststephen.org/ Guild of St. Stephen], accessed 21 March 2018</ref>\n* Saint Stephen is one of the sculptures on the side of the [[Orsanmichele]] in [[Florence, Italy|Florence]]. Saint Stephen is the patron saint of the [[Guilds of Florence|wool guild]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[Portal:Catholic Church/Patron Archive/December 26|Saint Stephen, patron saint archive]]\n* [[Guilds of Florence]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Saint Stephen}}\n{{Wikiquote|Stephanus}}\n* [http://www.bartleby.com/210/12/261.html \"Saint Stephen, the First Martyr\"]\n* [http://orthodoxwiki.org/Apostle_Stephen_the_Protomartyr \"Apostle Stephen the Protomartyr\"]\n* [http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/st.-stephens-death-shows-importance-of-scripture-pope-says/ Benedict XVI, \"Reflection on the Life and Death of Saint Stephen\"]\n* [http://www.stpetersbasilica.info/Exterior/Colonnades/Saints/St%20Stephen-98/StStephen.htm Colonnade Statue in St Peter's Square]\n* {{Hl-Lex|b|Stephanus.htm}}\n\n{{Catholic saints}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{History of the Catholic Church}}\n{{New Testament people}}\n{{History of Christianity}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Stephen, Saint}}\n[[Category:1st-century births]]\n[[Category:34 deaths]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:Early Jewish Christians]]\n[[Category:Roman-era Jews]]\n[[Category:People executed for heresy]]\n[[Category:People executed by stoning]]\n[[Category:People in Acts of the Apostles]]\n[[Category:Wonderworkers]]\n[[Category:Visions of Jesus and Mary]]\n[[Category:Burials at San Lorenzo fuori le Mura]]\n[[Category:Christian martyrs]]\n", "name_user": "GoingBatty", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Disambiguation help needed for one link -Palestine, 4 to be fixed -Palestine,Saint Etienne (disambiguation),St. Stephen's Cathedral (disambiguation),St. Stephen's Church (disambiguation)/WP:WCWproject (Spelling and typography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Stephen"}
{"title_page": "Kush Arora", "text_new": "{{External links|date=November 2012}}\n\n'''Kush Arora''' is a [[music producer]] and dj from [[San Francisco]]. His path through music draws influence from his beginnings around age 12 with industrial, metal, punk, goth, [[bhangra (music)|bhangra]]. In the late 1990s his focus shifted to experimental, dub, and dancehall inspired creations. By the early 2000s Kush's productions have found a unique and special place in the swarm of reggae, tropical, and cultural bass music landscape of today. He refined his booming, percussive aesthetic as a punk band drummer and cultivated his subversive sound-design principles from his industrial projects.\n\nIn 2012 he started a radio show called Surya Dub Radio on Berekley's KPFA 94.1FM Radio, California's largest independent station with Maneesh The Twister.\nHis current work is under the name Only Now, which combines cyberpunk aesthetics with kuduro, industrial, and tribal experimental sounds and synthesis.\n\n<ref name=\"sf\">\nKush Arora\n{{cite news\n|title=Kush Arora\u2019s sonic conflicts\n|first=Ron\n|last= Nachmann\n|date=2009-10-07\n|newspaper=SF Weekly\n|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2009-10-07/music/kush-arora-s-sonic-conflicts/\n}}</ref><ref name=\"mix\">\n{{cite news\n|title=Project Studio: Embarka Studios\n|date=2009-03-01\n|first= Matt\n|last=Gallagher\n|newspaper=Mix\n|url=http://mixonline.com/studios/profiles/project-studio-embarka-studios/\n}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n* Underwater Jihad (2004)<ref name=\"sf\"/>\n* Bhang Ragga  (2006)<ref>\n{{cite news\n|title=I Got Riddim Dr. Israel and Heavyweight Dub Champion at the Knitting Factory\n|first=Greg\n|last=Burk Wednesday\n|date=2006-03-15\n|newspaper=LA Weekly\n|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2006-03-16/music/i-got-riddim/\n}}</ref>\n\n*The Sludge - Various - Ghos Busters III (2007)\n*Hermetico (Dub Gabriel/Kush Arora Remix) Balkan Beat Box - Nu-Made (2008) ( J dub recordings)\n* From Brooklyn to SF ( 2009)\n* Dub Element